,Not Recommended,265300,33176654,Posted: 3 July,all,Ａｒｃｈｄｕｋｅ,"Whoever did the character models and armour/weapon design, very well done. Seriously, every piece I found looked great. It's a shame it was let down by nearly every other aspect. I only stuck it out for a couple of hours but there's still plenty of things that showed up and made it a bad experienceCons:-Combat is very slow and cumbersome even with the lighter weapons, and there's no animation cancelling, feels overall very clumsy.-Animation is a bit iffy, they make a point of taking your helmet off for the cutscenes but your face only has basic movements and the mouths aren't synced with the speech.-Very linear, there's only one actual path, there are technically other paths but they're all just a corrider leading to a room with a chest and some trash mobs that then lead straight back to the main path.-For a game clearly trying to be a SoulsLike it was very easy, I didn't come close to dying for the first two bosses and any of the mobs between them.-Not very well thought out, for instance there is a equipment weight system that affects how easily you move but it seems to base it purely off what chest piece you were wearing, so you could equip a 'Heavy' helm, boots, and gauntlets with the biggest weapon and shield you could manage and as long as you wore a 'Light' chest piece you can flip about like an acrobat.-There is backstabbing/parrying but its inconsistent if you're invulnerable or not during, some attacks hit you and some don't.-This one is just a pet peeve of mine, but it has the thing where you have to hold a button down for a short time to activate anything, which always sucks anyway but it's especially poorly done here, being quite innacurate and awkward.-While they look impressive and varied most weapons function much the same as eachother within the same catagory, and there was always a new one with clearly superiour stats so the other are rendered completely worthless within minutes of finding it.Pros:-3D Models look amazing-Hitboxes seem fairly good-Story could be interesting from the short bit I sawIt really feels like they had a bunch of left over assets from a failed project and stitched them together with an inexperienced team, it's a shame really, if only it had more time and care spent on it it could have been a nice little game."
,Recommended,265300,22761234,"Posted: 2 May, 2016",all,Mendhak,"Originally the 'mixed' rating had put me off, but I decided to try this during a sale.In a way that was a good thing, going in with low expectations and being pleasantly surprised.  The things that made me happy about it:Good graphicsGorgeous environmentsFramerate not capped at 30 (ahem)Difficult mobs/bossesAn actual storylineI had a read through many of the negative reviews and a lot of it is down to personal frustrations.  While in some places the game is actually quite unforgiving, I didn't think it warranted such negativity - difficulty spikes and overcoming them are part of the excitement of playing games like these.  The lesson I learned here was to take these Steam ratings with a pinch of salt.But to each their own, I will say - if you like fantasy-setting style games with difficult yet rewarding fights, try this out.I would advise you to have a look at a class guide first - I went in as a Solace Rogue and had a very tough time at some places but did manage to complete."
76561197985315581,Not Recommended,265300,12745693,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,Toohax,"The game is great but the product is defective.I haven't completed my first play through of Lords of the Fallen because I simply haven't been able to.  Not because the game is too difficult or too long but rather because of endless crashes.  My first save file was ruined by a death loop bug that rendered the file completely unusable.  I looked to see if there was a solution or if others had experienced it.  A few had and some even were able to get out of it by rolling their character immediately upon loading.  ""OK"" I thought, ""It was only 10 hours on that file, no big deal.""  Now on my second play through (after having twiddled with the settings per all the common temporary fix threads out there) I just can't play for more than 10 minutes without a crash.This is particularly problematic in a game in which one of the core mechanics is gambling for bigger rewards by not saving your game.  This, in itself, is a fun mechanic- I like the idea of having to risk your progress in the game for incremental rewards.  It's clever and potentially fun.  This is undermined entirely by the reality that bugs and crashes incentivize me to save as often as possible.There are good things about this game, a lot of them.  The art is amazing, the game feel is heavy in a visceral way that connects you to what you're doing.  I can't recommend it until it's been fixed, however.  I can't even play it.  With a GTX780 and similarly big specs throughout the rest of my rig, there's no excuse why these glitches, crashes, and bugs should exist.  This game was simply not tested thoroughly enough. I hope the developers will 1- fix the bugs asap and 2- learn their lesson so that their talents aren't overshadowed by sloppy mistakes.Update 1: I have pushed through to NG+ perhaps due to a desire to harm myself.Update 2: I'm looking forward to the new patch which promises to fix stability issues; I will expand my thoughts.Update 3: So far, so good.  Played for several hours without any stability issues.  Will get through NG+ before I decide to turn the frown upside down.  Clearly I'm enjoying the game a great deal or else I wouldn't be playing it.  It's still not for everyone."
76561198086112539,Recommended,265300,22506178,"Posted: 18 April, 2016",all,Dr Van Nostrand 47,"Deserves better reviews than it has. Apparently was riddled with bugs when released (lots of crashing, poorly optimised), but I had no problems running it on high settings with a modest mid-range rig (i5 3570k, AMD 7870, 8GB RAM). It also gets compared to Dark Souls a lot, and rightly so, but I don't think any game should be negatively reviewed for being 'not as good as Dark Souls', as that's a pretty high bar. So without further ado, lets dive right in and compare it directly to Dark Souls!Similar to Souls:Checkpoint system, red floating crystals instead of bonfires. Replenish HP / MP / potions, enemies respawn.Melee combat mechanics - parry (only with subset of shields), backstabs, stamina management, dodgerolls, staggering, light attack, heavy attack, running attack etc. Similar range of weapons. % Equipment load determines movement and dodgeroll speed. 'Weighty' feel to larger weapons.Weapons (but not armour) have stat requirements. Some weapons scale with their relevant stat.Loot - set loot gained through chests, enemies have a chance of dropping 'runes' (for upgrades) or equipment (rare). No duplicate armour / weapons.Level design - sprawling areas that loop back into each other by unlocking shortcuts. Lots of secret items and areas.Leveling - bank experience at checkpoints to level up attributes / spells, each subsequent level requires more.Upon death your exp is left as a 'ghost' with a timer on it, or until your next death.NG+ and NG++ for multiple playthroughs.Decimate furniture by rolling into itDifferent from SoulsNo fast travel from checkpoint to checkpoint, not a massive problem because;Smaller world, fast traveling would have been nice at times, but overall not a big problem.Shorter game, could be finished in maybe 8 hours if you don't explore much. Personally it took me around 15 hours.No invincibility during dodgeroll that I am aware of. Causes some moments of anger if you're used to Dark Souls, but you get used to it.Magic - each class (warrior, thief, cleric) has a set of 4 spells that can be unlocked and leveled up at checkpoints, separately from attribute points. There is also a gauntlet that has 3 modes of fire (basically different ranges), which gains power with more Faith (cleric / magic build). Both share an MP pool.Much more straightforward story, quite typical dark fantasy stuff, not too abstract or anything.Equipment upgrading is done through a 'rune' system - you gain sealed runes from defeating enemies, and unlock them to reveal type (eg power / fire / luck), runes range from 'lesser' to 'flawless' and can be attached and detached at will from equipment that has slots.No multiplayer aspectOther notes: The game looks great - dark atmosphere, good enemy/boss design, weapons / armour look suitably fantasy, so you get that extra bit of satisfaction from new gear. The melee combat is heavily emphasised, ranged combat is minimal (pretty much limited to gauntlet). Many weapon types have very slow attack speed, which can take a bit of getting used to, but there are claws and daggers for faster attacks (this is how I played) which are perfectly viable. It is not as big or complex as Dark Souls, but still holds it's own as a solid Action-RPG with dark fantasy flavour, good melee combat, and some side quests and extra exploration encouraged to flesh out the experience.All in all I really enjoyed my time playing Lords of the Fallen, and seeing as you can get it for disgustingly cheap when it's on sale these days, I don't see why you shouldn't pick it up."
76561198060983111,Recommended,265300,30903888,Posted: 2 April,all,Ateia,"Criminally underrated game, The majority of the negative review this game gets are from ppl comparing it to the game it drew influence from (Dark Souls) and expecting the mechanics to be a carbon copy which they are not.Combat feels more heavy and impactful and it uses hitbox angles to a bigger extend (enemies with shield might seem OP until you realize you can jump attack and angle your weapon so it hits above the shield etc).If you are a ds player don't expect to wear heavy armor a gs and be able to dodge and attack out of a roll, you can attack out of a roll but only with lighter weapons.of course the game is not perfect theres not that much variety  with the enemies and the look of the areas, magic in this game is more for support that instead been able to do magic builds.If you like ARPG you should try this out, is really way better than people make it out to be."
