76561198289373353,Recommended,265300,26076115,"Posted: 16 October, 2016",all,Sanjuboy,"A Very Good Game UnderratedAfter completing the game just now, I cannot refrain from writing anything but a positive review when there are so many negative ones here bringing the rating of this game down which is real injustice and a shame. Sure the game lacks Dark souls level of polish and there is the issue of crashes when the fighting gets a little too intense during certain boss fights and especially when magic spells are used too often in such scenarios but this in my opinion does not take away all the goodness this game offers overall. Being a carbon copy of Dark Souls in most aspects, Lords of the Fallen starts feeling like an entirely different game after a few hours. With a decent story, great graphics with spectacular lighting and particle effects, clever use of magic, tricky side-quests, hidden secrets and npc interactions, it creates an experience which is different from the Souls series which actually is a good thing in my opinion. LOTF is an easier version of Dark Souls with a merrier environment - much for the pleasure of a casual gamer though still only a Souls fan would connect to. First timers with no prior induction to Dark Souls kind of gameplay might find this game tough enough for few bouts of frustration.The graphics and lighting are really good and almost all armors are intricate in design. The music is satisying, voice acting good but the animations that support it look stiff most of the time. Combat feels strikingly similar to Dark Souls with identical button mapping on the gamepad which is a good thing for a Souls player. The loot is diverse and a few of the weapons and shields are awesome. For example, a shield called 'Twisted Ways' (DLC content) has a rotating map on it. How cool is that? Talking about map, the overall size of the game world known as Keystone is quite big and most of the time would leave you scratching your head as to how to get to a particular spot which had a locked chest that you now found a key to. With twisted dungeons hiding secrets, a castle holding plenty of hidden areas and a portal to a whole new dimension, the whole process of exploring every nook and corner can be daunting.Enemies and Bosses aren't that tough compared to Dark Souls and what I like most about them in LOTF is there is a knack in taking them down. Ofcourse, Dark Souls has it written all over it but in some areas in LOTF, especially in one or two boss fights you might want to think out-of-the box to avoid taking damage which is something spectacular when you discover it yourself. However, some boss fights are crash-riddled if you do not own a beefy PC and the DLC boss is such a pain to beat. End of the day, bad optimization is where the game loses at and If it weren't for this it would've received rave reviews for sure.Simply put, this game might fall short on optimizations but it is a very good game if your PC can power it. Following the footsteps of Dark Souls and yet bringing a whole new feel within is purely refreshing. LOTF is best played with keeping Dark Souls' gameplay in mind and might do enough to frustrate newcomers. But to those who are well acquainted with the Souls series, LOTF is yet another epic journey.To sum it up:+ Good Graphics- Needs a beefy PC+ Varied Loot- Some areas require polish+ Interesting Secrets/ Replayability- Can be frustrating to the uninitiatedMY SCORE: 80/100"
76561198084657727,Not Recommended,265300,19367838,"Posted: 29 November, 2015",all,Celtic Steel,"Ok, ok, this review has gone through a few iterations so bear with me people.When I first played LOTF, I absolutely despised it.  Being a big fan of the Souls games, I was looking forward to some Souls-esque but-without-getting-stomped-by-overpowerd-invasions fun.  But dang, Harken was slow and seemed to spend about 10 seconds winding up his attacks before actually throwing them, and I quickly grew bored of this game and its unresponsive controls.  So, my first review was rather scathing, and lo many a fan boy/girl posted some rather immature and insulting comments, most of which have been deleted.  I’m a stoopid noob and I should go back to candy crush saga, apparently.  I also need to 'git gud' even though the difficulty of this game (which isn't much) was never an issue...Being a cheapskate and wanting to get my money’s worth out of the game, I forced myself to complete.  And you know what?  LOTF is not a bad game.  I might even have enjoyed it a wee bit.  But I would not recommend this game unless it is on sale – because there are much better games (i.e. Dark Souls) which do everything LOTF does only much better.Still, LOTF is bloody gorgeous, looking like Todd Macfarlane and Warhammer Fantasy got together to make a Cannibal Corpse album cover.  The armour and weapon designs are so ludicrously spikey and evil that I want to break out my old Slayer albums.  Sound is also great, with satisfying clunks and crashes giving combat a satisfying feel.  The bosses are super cool too.  I also particularly liked the system up upgrading weapons and armour with runes, which is very simple but kinda nice anyway.However, I found the controls to feel really unresponsive.  No matter what class you play as, there’s a significant lag between actually hitting the attack button and Harken swinging whatever oversized spike metal thingy he is carrying.  It lead me to a lot of frustration, as I signed in vain while the enemy would rush off for a cup of tea, do the washing, then come back and put their shield up in the time it takes Harken to wind up his attack.  Second, the game is not really challenging, and it doesn’t have difficulty settings.  Most enemies can be overpowered just by circling endlessly and button mashing, and many of the bosses can be easily beaten on first try once their attack pattern has been seen a few times.  I understand that NG+ is more of a challenge, but I’d already lost interest by then.In summary, my opinion, which you don’t have to agree with, is that LOTF is an ok Dark Souls-lite game, but I wouldn’t recommend it because Dark Souls, even Dark Souls 2, does EVERYTHING infinitely better aside from graphics.  Furthermore, if I’m in the mood for some fantasy hack and slash and I’m not in the mood for Dark Souls, I’d play Devil May Cry, Darksiders 2, Dragons Dogma, Revengence or something long before I’d go for LOTF.  but hey there seems to be a lot of ppl who really loved this...what does a stoopid noob like me know anyway? git gud or go home...Edit - Now that Dark Souls 3 is out there is no need to even contemplate this game.  Or go with Salt and Sanctuary if your a 2d indie hispter - that said, if they make a sequel i'd give it a look as, if they got the gameplay right, this could easily be the Slayer album cover made flesh the never-dying 12 year old inside me is always looking for."
