a ""Fire Rune"" onto my weapon would make it burst into flames and set enemies on fire; nope. Only truly useful rune was the the attribute scaling one which doubled my 2h output to be able to put out enough DPS to kill the final boss on NG+ after over 12 attempts.-NG+ = shards for loot or you pick up any armor from the chests that you missed on your first playthrough. Incredibly boring-I genuinely expect to continue to progress my character throughout ALL playthroughs and leveling up my character in NG+ was a damn grind and chore beyond what I would have expected.I expected more. I bought into the hype and the game failed to meet my expectations. Im an experienced gamer. Ive been playing games through my days ever since NES. Im no stranger to game mechanics and progression.Get it if you want it, but dont expect to be floored unless you have low expectations and standards. I wish I would have waited for sale.UPDATE-2(Slight Spoilerish);;From what I have read playing as a warrior is generally considered to be the easiest form of play. This is using a shield and possibly a 2-handed weapon. I use this setup. I decided to jump back in and play a bit more on NG+. I have reached the Citadel and have noticed a large jump in damage to my character. I am using the heaviest set of armor with the best defense stats and a tyrant in the graveyard nearly one-shotted me with his overhead swing. It was a genuine ""WTF"" moment.Needless to say that I was quite suprised. I continued playing a bit more and noticed sharp rises of damage intake during set points. The catacombs boss proved an interesting challenge as he hit quite a bit harder which is something I was not used to. I actually died on the giant boss that you eventually meet in the area of the three statutes. He hit quite hard.I am not picking up anymore armor on NG+ which leads me to believe that because my defense stats will generally not improve except whenever I mod them fully with runes that I have picked up throughout the game and because the damage intake is steadily and sometimes sharping increasing as I get towards end-game sections; I do feel that perhaps NG++ will truly be where the actual difficulty lies that people most want concerning this game.Its a matter of deduction based on the information available. This is with the best defense AND without using spells. As such, I am now actually looking forward to NG++ to see just how punishing this game truly is.Also, because of the high defense given by heavy armor...this means that medium and light armor wearers will face significantly more damage and possibly one-shots on several abilities given by several mobs. This is not considering any defensive advantages given by the magic system in this game. It is purely utilizing armor and weapons.I have currently 13 potion slots and I find myself using them more and more. That is a good sign. I will update when I finally experience NG++UPDATE;After playing through NG+ to the halfway to 75% point I must say that I have to change my review to being recommended only if your dead set on getting a game that is similar to the DS series or waiting for a sale or unless your out-right starved for something new and exciting.Unless you enjoy the story and are set on keeping the same playthrough running as much as you can then you will not find hardly anything at all to keep you engaged with the game after beating it the first time...unless you want to make different choices to affect the ending slides; but you could just watch youtube, right?I saw the vids on youtube and even the tips during the loading screen. They said you will get new loot and stuff on subsequent playthroughs. The only thing that I have noticed are new lore drops specifically in the regions on normal that were not there but were then there on NG+As with regards to armor/weapons? I did pick up a light armor set which seems to be the rogue counterpart to the last heavy armor set I picked up for warriors. I could have missed it on my first playthrough, however, so this isnt saying much. I went through this entire experience of NG picking up shards 95-99% of the time. Very underwhelming.My thoughts are that what was promoted is not what was essentially delivered to a satisfying context.Im disappointed. The combat is good, but I feel that long-lasting value is lacking to this game and that is a damn shame.For the first playthrough, however, it was a blast."
76561198061403132,Recommended,265300,31362849,Posted: 25 April,all,Kyousuke Azai,"Being an somewhat of a fan of the Souls franchise, I've heard a lot of things about this game, most of them, as I've found out, untrue. Lords of The Fallen (further only as LoTF) gets a lot and I mean a LOT of flak for, copying dark souls, being way too hard/way too easy/way too clunky. Well I went into it expecting what it is, clunky souls and boy was I surprised. So let's get a few things straight.Combat - It's slow, really slow, even one handed weapons take longer than your average two-hander in dark souls, that's not even mentioning the really big stuff, this game loves its big and metal things, so much so that some weapons are so heavy in fact, you can't even use them one handed, not even with proper stats, now that's a weapon. So for you guys out there who breezed through dark souls via R1 spams, you are not going to have a lot of fun here. Certain enemies demand certain tactics, hell there is an enemy that will smash you into the ground over and over again until you learn how to parry, really loved that one. Speaking of which, yes, your usual suspects of light/heavy attacks are here with your backstabs and parries, giving the combat a nice depth, really forcing you to learn how to fight your enemies and see the openings.Theme - As mentioned above, this game goes in big, hard and metal. You can wear outrageous amounts of armour and you will be moving at the speed of snails and fat roll everywhere, BUT, you can clear the game just as well doing that as if you go for light armor and dodge everything. I've really felt powerful being able to shake off big hits as minor bother. So unlike in any other souls-like game, here, heavy armor is actually a legitimate choice and a welcome one at that, I've had unbelievable amounts of fun crushing through enemies with a 2 handed axe, effectively making some of them into a wet spot on the floor.Story - Honestly, not the strongest point, you can take it or leave it, there is plenty to know about the world and how it came to be if you choose to hunt for audio bits and bops or you can ignore them and skip through most of it, so unfortunately this one might be one of the weaknesses. It doesn't have that ""I wanna know more"" pull to it, but is still enjoyable enough as short as it is.Performance - Oh yeah, this one...yeah... clunky is the best I could put it, frame rate drops on a fairly powerful rig for today's standards, texture pop-in, few enemies joining the space program and rocketing off into space, oddly stiff and stood upright weapons, leading to more than a few morning wood jokes, you get the idea, it's not gamebreaking, but it's not quite what it should be.Overall, I'd say this game is definitely worth 20 bucks, it's difficult, but fun as it is meant to be. I can see myself clearing it a few more times to see all the secrets and find all the armor sets and challenges. So if you enjoy yourself a bit of challenge yourself, but not so much of it to be overwhelming and want to feel like a buldozer let loose in a cardboard box this might just be the game you might enjoy."
