,Not Recommended,265300,12678639,"Posted: 29 October, 2014",all,Severen,"UPDATE: beaten the game and all opinions below still apply, honestly (I was about 8 hours in when i wrote this impression). I can say that if you don't like Demons/Dark Souls, you will more than likely doubly-dislike this game. So just to get that right out in front, don't look for this game to change your opinion on the Souls-style gaming, because it wont.Now to people who are looking for a Souls-like experience, in my honest opinion, you shouldNOTget your hopes up. While the game has an overall Souls feel when it comes to combat, as Lords of the Fallen (LotFfrom this point on) seems to borrowVERYheavily from the game, it's about as far from Souls-FEELINGas it could be given how closely the mechanics work.The game- isSLOW.Like, ""snail trudging through molasses in winter-time"" slow. In every aspect that a game can be considered slow, LotF is. Player movement is slow, attack animations are slow, roll speed is slow, gauntlet attacks are slow, spell startups are slow- hell even the story is slow, but I'll talk about that later.If you go into this game thinking you're going to play it like anything other than that fat-rolliest heavy armored monster-weapon-wielding tank in Dark Souls, then you're going in with expectations far exceeding what the game allows. Unfortunately, it seems that many of the enemies and a few ofSOMEenemies attacks seem to be designed entirely around blocking the hit and then countering after their animation is done- which is fine for the most part, but when LotF advertises dual-wielding fast weapons and light armor with the option to dodge roll away from enemies, it's NOT fine. The level of reaction time a person would need to dodge some enemies moves borders on precognition, and this is coming from a Darks Souls 1 and 2 vet (nearly 800 hours combined with both games across PC and Xbox 360).Not only that, but many enemies haveRIDICULOUSLY GOODtracking on their moves. Which is GREAT for THEM, but sucks [b♥♥♥♥♥♥/b] for the player. Take all of the complaints of Dark Souls 2 humanoid enemies having auto-tracking overheads and you can apply that to almost every enemy in the game with nearly every attack. Granted you can still dodge them, just like in Dark 2, but it's still difficult, and if you're anything but fast rolling, the chances of you rolling far enough to be out of range of their next auto-tracking attack is slim. Take one of the later bosses for example- The Infiltrator.VERY MINOR SPOILERSI dodge the first attack of her hit string, by rollingUNDERher, only to have her INSTANTLY turn around and hit me with her second swing because I could not roll far enough away from her.Very, very poor design. I wont get into the fight itself until later.The enemies in this game so far (as I said, about 8 hours in) are almost all humanoid. So circle-strafing almost completely nullifies the lesser enemies as a threat, which is fine. However, some of the enemies later on end up having such good tracking that it's nearly impossible to get around their shield. This wouldn't be a problem if after guard-breaking them with a kick my attack animation was fast enough to hit them before they recovered but sadly with just about anythingother thanclaws or daggers, it was not fast enough, and I was left fighting a frustrating battle of ""wait until they attack and try to move in before they recover"" which also proved incredibly difficult. Okay, so how about blocking with my shield and allowing them to suffer recoil from their blow and sticking them then?Nope.They recovered before my hit landed and blocked it.OKAY.HOW ABOUT I JUST SIT HERE AND HOLD MY SHIELD UP UNTIL AN OPENING PRESENTS ITSELF.ahahahaha- no. He guard breaks me with a shield slam that is almost faster than my brain can even register and then follows up immediately with a slash that takes down 3/4's of my health bar. Mind you- this is all ONE ENEMY- but it's the perfect example to what I feel is just bad enemy design in general. You want to make your enemies hard, cool give it some of the counters above, but not ALL of them. I literally had to just run away from the damn things until my mana filled up enough to allow me to burst him with my gauntlet- which took 4 hits (and if you've played the game, just after you get the gauntlet, getting in 4 gauntlet blasts can take a long freakin' time with the slow mana recharge and how much it costs early game). Not only that- there were 3 of these enemies in the area, sort of following the same corridor.Hurrayyyy. I beat them but I was not at all happy with what I had to resort to in order to do so- for the gauntlet to be the ONLY reliable way to deal with them at that point just was not fun- at all.As for the monster designs, they're fairly simple. They don't do much poise damage, they mostly stagger off your shield, and some do fire or poison damage but it's all pretty standard stuff. Nothing to complain about, nothing to praise.Boss designs-SPOILERS AHEADSo many of you probably know that the first two bosses are tower-shield users. Basically you wait for them to attack and either dodge or block and retaliate. Standard stuff, nothing to talk about with the first one... The SECOND tower shield boss- summonsadds. Which, if you're a Souls fan, you are probably of the same opinion as I am, that adding adds to your boss fight is basically admitting that 'yeah, we didn't know how to make the fight hard or interesting, so worry about these ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥s screwing with you while you're fighting this brainless boss"". Now I make an exception for this one, because the boss does not stay active while the adds are out, so you fight the adds and then go back to the boss- fine, whatever. Pointless? Sure. Harmful? Not really, it's fine. Now beyond that is where it starts getting irritating. The next boss I fought killed me a few times by doing an AOE attack that covers the whole entire arena. He has a startup and once you know what comes after the start up, you know what's on it's way- but the first time, you'rescrewed. Cheap death, cheap gimmick and utterly pointless once you figure out WHERE you're supposed to stand, which is not exactly made apparent when your first instinct is just to avoid the blue bulbs and hide somewhere they're not near. On top of that- he summons adds. Same with the next boss, Infiltrator. Adds, heals itself, mana is being sapped.. otherwise a boring fight with only a few actual attacks.The level design is-okay.The game does take the open world aspect of Dark Souls 1 with areas looping back and creating shortcuts from other areas- but the problem is going THROUGH the areas is pretty linear. It's much more akin to something like Dark Siders 1 level design where you go the way they want you to go and then loop back around when you acquire a thing that you needed to get into an area you couldn't before- which is really just to create theILLUSIONof an open world game. On top of that, in my first few hours of the game, I saw just blatant copies of previous areas with just a few minor furnishing adjustments and enemy placements. Pretty lazy. However, the ART style is really nice, if you're into that Diablo-esque ""hardcore metal hellspawn"" style- which I am, aha.If all that wasn't enough to spook you, the game has performance issues. My PC runs  Shadows of Mordor on max settings without a stutter, this game drops inexplicably below 30 FPS constantly, and sometimes lower- and that's with settings set down on what are described as, or would be considered ""medium."" Very disappointing.Story is the most barebones ""i'm a tough guy"" story you could have. Don't come to LotF looking for anything more.Sorry. Can't recommend this game so far..."
