76561198009512978,Recommended,265300,24067699,"Posted: 3 July, 2016",all,Captain Metal,"TL;DR: Buy Lords of the Fallen if you have a decent PC to run it onA lot of people bash this game, as you can probably see up there under the user reviews percentages.Most of those people are folks that live, breathe, eat and sleep Dark Souls or one of the other souls games in general (or bought it on launch day, more on that in a minute ) and as a result they spew bad reviews at it simply because its a similar game/competition, not harcore enough or simply ""Not the same!"", Its rather unfortunate really.Lords of the Fallen was really buggy on launch, like game destroying buggy, but now all of those bugs have been fixed and now the game works flawlessly. Having put 20+ hours into it I havent encountered a single bug or issue since it was patched up, like this ""animation lag"" or ""crash"" people falsely throw at this game nowadays ( once again, to make it less appealing than a Souls game because of blatant bias )Having a high end of average rig, I get a super stable 60fps when playing, and not only does it run smoothly the game looks amazing, so amazing on ultra, especially with its later armour designs  that frankly Im disapointed that Dark Souls 3 didnt end up looking this good. Animation quality with the exception of one or two characters is great and frankly its one of the few games wearing a cape actually looks cool as opposed to it looking like a sack of buggy Gmod crap.Gameplay and combat are pretty much what you expect, its a souls style game, a big open-ish area to area world. Combat consists of the usual light attack, heavy attack, block and then a parry/special shield move, also with a block-breaker, spriting, rolling and jump/lunge attacks. Dodging works just fine but heavier armour makes your dodge less viable etc etc, less emphasis on range, though you do get a ranged weapon eventually.Kill bad guys and fight a boss, if you die you lose all your experience until you can go visit the spot where you died to get said experience back, die again and its all gone. Stats n' the like work a little differently, but the idea behind them is the same, use gained EXP to level up, but if you hold onto your experience without visiting and saving your progress at a checkpoint you gain a multiplier to your EXP, which is good when you need to farm for levels and cuts out on some that needless busy-work time.While Lords doesnt have any multiplayer components, it places more emphasis on the story, and while the narrative is 'okay' thats where it all falls short. The main characters themselves with the exception of your main guy Harken, are sort've shoddily done. But there is dialogue choices and lil' sidequests where you have to make a decision that affects the reward you gain at the end. If you dont care so much about narrative as you do gameplay, you wont mind how bad the story is that much.Bosses are fun, each one with a little secret 'extra' way to beat them to gain a boss-item/weapon from them, the secrets can be fun to find even if some of them are somewhat missable or hard to figure out. Quest-lines, hidden secret weapons and armour, runes to upgrade you weapons and armours with, its all just filled with really good stuff.If you have a decent rig/desktop PC to run it on, and you want something new and fresh from the Dark Souls monotony, then just buy Lords of the Fallen,"
