,Recommended,265300,23452257,"Posted: 8 June, 2016",all,CitizenX3639,"Thank you to Deck13 and CI games for development and publishing Lords of The Fallen. I enjoyed the world and charcters you provided for me to escape.As i end my run of LOTF during new game + and reflect my on experience it reminds me of a successful turn-based game(Aarklash Legacy) that stripped away a lot of ""trending"" RPG systems to the bone while focusing more on gameplay. I think thats exactly what LOTF also has done though with mixed results but it has more me excited for a sequel rather than another Dark Souls.LOTF is a 3rd person action game in which you play as Harken(no charcter custimization) a criminal that has been sprung from jail from a mysterious monk named Kaslo. Kaslo insist you are the one to defeat the evil rhogar and the revived God Adyr as it takes evil to slay evil. Though Harken wears his crimes on his face with markings(very cool)it is only mentioned briefly from a run in with a guard and we never know what crimes he committed. A big opportunity missed in that regard. Along this story quest you will face a few decisions that will decide one of three possible endings. Its a good video game story with good voice acting but none of it was memorable. Its all pretty standard by now, but more effort is here than expected and its actually a story rather than pieces and speculation.Once you start the game you are only given 3 classes to choose the cleric, warrior, and rouge which for story reasons makes sense. All charcters have pre made stats so custimization is minimal. I chose the rouge class which from my understanding is considered hard mode and at the start it is very diffcult as a slight breeze seemed to kill me. Fortunantley you are able to level quickly but it took a good 10 hrs before i felt powerful. Leveling your character is pretty normal as you slay enemies and complete quests you are rewarded with XP which you will distribute through either upgrading your magic(4 spells x 3 upgrades) or physical (6 options STR/VIT/END/FAITH/AGI/LUCK). Again comapared to a lot of RPGs these upgrades while minimal i think actually made it easier to maintain the specific charcter you envisioned at the start.Gaining experience does come with its caveat of risk and reward. In LOTF the longer you stay alive and kill enemies a multiplier for XP will continue to increase(x2.0 max) and If you die your 'ghost' will be waiting for you to return. However, your ghost will dissolve based on the stregnth of the multiplier. The larger the multiplier the longer it will be visible and at 100%. I like this idea but it is basically null becasue of checkpoints are located everywhere. I can only think of one instance where i was not able to retrieve my ghost and it was just a dumb mistake on my part.LOTF also does not follow todays trend with a massive open world but a more confined semi linear castle exploration design. This made for walking around slow and steady and some of the levels are good but late near the end game i was totally lost and could not recall where to go. Dont be mistaken there are some levels that are outdoors but for the most part action is in tight hallways. The level and quest design also plays into LOTF no hand holding policiy which i love but if you want to make it easier on your self keep notepad and pen close.Not suprising as with any title today i recall LOTF did have some launch issues with some bugs and graphical glitches but other than a crash or 2 the game played and looks amazing. The envorments, weapons, enemies and charcters all have a heavy metal vibe and the sound design maybe some of the best for this type of genre i have heard. The thud of weapons against shields, echoes in the caverns and just the wind blowing all make for a very immersive experience.As a rouge i moved fast and with the spells available i was pretty powerful late in game but getting in close against enemies was high risk. However a majority of fighting is always one on one so encounters are not too difficult. I pretty much used either daggars or these awesome wolverine like claws  as weapons and late in the game i found out somthing i did not know. Without spoilers it basically changed everything about my charcter and i suddenly became a real bad♥♥♥♥♥  If LOTF has its 'thing' its these hidden secrets about weapons, bosses and quests. After i completed the game and found out some of the secrets i was suprised how deep and how many there actually are becasue in In game you would never know.After my initial playthrough i started up new game + which a rarely do but becasue i wanted to see if any higher gear would drop and i was really dissapointed. Enemies and loot did not scale and i basically walked through the first 4 bosses without a scartch. If it did scale who knows i proabably would still be playing.LOTF is a good new action RPG that compliments other titles in the genre but seperating itself in some new and exciting ways.  It doesnt follow todays RPG trends of needing a huge open world, 100hr campaign, and deep crafting system it relys on good ol' game and gameplay and that is always welcome in my librbary.PositivesA solid 3rd person action RPG game that doesnt take 100 hrs to completeEnviroments, weapons, charcters and enemies look greatSound design is incredibleNice clean UINo hand holdingLevel design is ok, but i would like to have seen the world more interconnectedSome bosses are greatA lot of 'hidden' content for quests, bosses and equipYou can break the game making it easyNegativesToo many Checkpoints decrease the tension, maybe an option to decrease for difficulty?Enemy varietySome bosses were very basic in design patternNo scaling for enemeis or loot in new game +the balance of enemies and spells  fells off- you are OPNot a lot of difference in spells from each type of charcter choiceCrafting is quite shallowInventory UI could be better-cant drop itemsNotes:I played on my desktop PC with an R9 390 video cardI have about 30+ hrs in one full playthough and upto the 4th boss on new game +I played the game at 1080P/ 60 running smooth with 1-2 crashesI used an Xbox controller"
,Not Recommended,265300,23566137,"Posted: 15 June, 2016",all,Brigand Boy,"Don't.The game looks pretty. It sounds pretty. The character development feels like it could be pretty.The combat though... isn't good. It's slightly clunky but managable at first, but then you run into an enemy with a tower shield and the fun just jumps out the window and the tedium sets in.It's a game that needs other options on how to deal with enemies, and pigeon-holes you into doing only one thing, regardless of what your spec happens to be. The fact that the rogue, for instance, needs FAITH to cast his spells (and be a rogue) should be a clue. The fact that a tank/warrior needs the same stat to cast HIS spells should also be a clue.The classes don't really work the way they need to.That's not even getting into how the combat feels, which is awkward.Weapons and characters do not interact as if they are in the same world. I feel like the animation happens, then damage somehow happens. I don't feel like the weapon is connecting with anything. The weapons certainly don't connect with the terrain, which is a shame.Weapon animations themsevles are largely dissapointing not just in visual appeal but also in practical use in combat. One of the first weapons you get is a greatsword from a boss, and it is arguably the best in damage for a strength based character but it is also almost useless due to it's slow animation speed and the fact that the move set is awkward in a fight.Dodges are completely useless. They are too short, the invulnerablity is too short, and enemies will follow you through a dodge and hit you anyway if they are charging.Sprinting is a pain in the butt on a controller. Holding down the same joystick you use to move is not a good idea for a sprint function. It's especially awkward since you need sprint to fight and you need sprint to JUMP. And jumping is required to get to certain areas.Leveling up takes too long and the rewards for leveling up aren't that interesting.Spells are limited and mostly boring at the start.Some enemies (especially those with shields) are tedious to the point of frustration because their guard can't be easily broken, dodging around them doesn't work (they stick to you and rotate very fast), the kick attack is erratic and unreliable, and they don't seem to lose stamina when you hit the shield. They certainly don't lose more stamina than you do, and you stagger yourself if you hit a shield anyway.The enemies animations always seem faster than yours, even when they are using a great weapon and you are using a 1h sword. For whatever reason, enemies always seem to interrupt your animation while it is very rare to interrupt theirs. This means you can be spammed to death by enemy attacks, while you cannot spam them to death. This is especially frustrating when dealing with multiple enemies at once. Gods help you if more than one of them has a shield, because using a strong sweeping attack certainly won't.There are more things to complain about, but they all center around the combat system and controls. The thing is, 99% of the game is the fighting, and the fighting itself is tedious and frustrating. Unlike in Dark Souls where if you beat a monster that has been giving you issues and you feel elation, in this game I feel nothing. Ultimately, it feels like I didn't win. I feel like the game just randomly allowed me to win. Skill doesn't appear to play a part in how the game goes, which is exactly the opposite of what I wanted out of this game.In short, don't buy it unless it is heavily discounted. I'm glad I waited and didn't get it at premium new release price ($50+) but I still feel that at $30 I could have spent my money elsewhere and been happier. The game looks really nice, but it doesn't play like a play-tested game. I feel like it was such a missed shot. They had everything they needed to give From a run for their money, but the one thing they didn't perfect bit them in the rear."
