76561197970603994,Not Recommended,265300,28022377,"Posted: 28 November, 2016",all,[SSO] Bleddyn,"Lords of the Fallen is, at it's core, a Dark Souls knock off. For those who think Dark Souls is a little more challenging than it's worth but love the idea, Lords of the Fallen is here for you.Mechanics:You start off by picking a generic class type: Brawling, Deception, and Solace (Warrior, Rogue, Mage). Each class type gets a unique set of 4 spells, with 3 levels within each spell type. Within these classes, there are sub class choices made up primarily by beginning stat variations. You level up your attributes by killing mobs, and gaining experience. You get an experience modifier that scales up the more enemies you kill without saving. Dying loses all experience, and you have to run back to your ghost and claim your ghost to regain lost experience.All class types can wear all types of armor, with a burden rate that slows down your character as it becomes more burdened. They can also use all types of weapons, but weapons have stat requirements that make most weapons outside of your class unlikely to be used. Occasionally mobs will drop runes that can be ""unsealed"" by a mystical ghost armorsmith to varying levels of usefulness (i.e. common luck rune vs. flawless luck rune). These can be slotted into armor and weapons for bonuses. There are a handful of trinkets that can also be equipped that are seeded throughout the world and add additional bonuses (more weight carrying, health regen, additional magic regen, etc.).Magic and Energy is used to cast spells and swing weapons respectively, with spells and weapons draining set amounts on casts. Once the bars are drained, the respective ability can no longer be used until it's regenerated.Armor and weapons never break, and can't be sold. They are collected, and stored and swapped out at any time (including mid battle). You also have a set number of potions that grows as you find more empty potion bottles, which can be refilled (partially) at save points (eerily similar to Dark Souls flasks and fires). In addition to potions, you are given consumables which grant fire resistance, energy points, etc. Energy and Magic regenerates but health does not.If all of that sounds pretty standard, that's because it is. Lords of the Fallen does not provide anything new, and instead provides a healthy dose of mediocre. It's like watching an action movie that you know wont be great, but you've watched all the good action movies already. You'll settle for that movie. It'll hit that craving, but you wont go out and tell your friends to go and watch it. That's Lords of the Fallen.Story **SPOILERS**:Where Dark Souls makes you curious about the world you're wandering around in, Lords of the Fallen teases it ever so slightly just enough for you to realize you (and likely the story writers) don't care at all about it. But you don't play Lords of the Fallen for the storyline. You play it to kill monsters.The game immediately throws you into the middle of a storyline, requiring you to suspend your belief and understand that a lot of things happened before you started this game, and you don't need to know about them, nor will you ever learn.Facts:1) You're a criminal (Harkyn)2) You're following a monk (Kaslo) who has apparently let you out of jail.3) They tattooed your face so others can recognize you as a criminal.Why did they let you out. You don't need to know. Why are you following this monk instead of just killing him and running off? You don't need to know. What did you do to land you in jail? You don't need to know.You start off right in the action, in Keystone Monastary, where Antanas the king of everything is holed up. You fight the Rhogar, a demonic race that is invading the human plane, and killing humans. You find out that Anatanas has found a way of seperating the evil of man from the good, leaving only the good, and it is hinted that this might be want has spawned the Rhogar.Kaslo lets you know that it is your duty to fight the Rhogar Lords. Throughout your journey you run into Yetka, another warrior in the area who is looking for ways to translate a book left to her by her parents in a different language.You fight your way through a number of bosses including the First Warden, Commander, and Worshipper (in the graveyard). The first two are fairly simply knight type bosses, with the Worshipper summoning demons that you can kill before they hatch. Once you kill this Demon, you enter... THE RHOGAR REALM. It's here you meet the Crafter, a floaty blackish ghost being whose evolved in the Rhogar Realm to travel dimensions. Who was he before he evolved? You don't need to know. You find out very little else about himIn the Rhogar Realm you kill some of the Rhogar Lords in order to stop the Rhogar invasion, so you do, and come back to planet.... not Rhogar. Here, you meet back up with Kaslo and fight your way back through the Rhogar's invading the Monastery to get to Antanas. Through audio clips picked up by floating scrolls you find out that Antanas is obsessed with evil after losing his wife, driving him mad. Kaslo seems to sense that something is wrong, telling you he will stay behind to investigate, while Antanas sends you back to the Rhogar Realm to kill the remaining Rhogar Lords, and draw out Adyr the god who controls them.So you go and kill the Rhogar lords back in the same map you used. You meet Yetka once again who is still deciphering her family text. Turns out it's written in Rhogar! You come upon a beast, and she implores you not to to kill it, because it can take her to her family. So for once, you show mercy, and let her take the time traveling beast back to her family.... and that's the end of her storyline. Why was she trying to find her family? You don't need to know.Finally you make it to Adyr, who shows you the ghosts of all the bosses you've defeated (with stats on how many times you died and how long it took you to kill them. Thanks Adyr!) and he tells you... (PLOT TWIST!!!) Antanas is the bad guy all along *dun dun dun*. He never shows up, and gives you a magical rune to use against Antanas to kill him, and let the Rhogar win once and for all. And so you... BUT WAIT! Kaslo shows up in ghost form, and reveals that he is in fact also a god, but a watcher, sent to restore balance.And then he sends you back to the Monastarey where you run into Ghost Crafter, the being you know  almost literally nothing about? He mentions offhandedly how pretty your new rune is, speaks a riddle, and presents you with a choice.  Do you forge the rune into your armor, your weapon, or just let him have it. Apparently this choice alone determines whether you let the humans win, the Rhogar win, or balance the world. Why does he need the rune to balance the world? Why him? You don't need to know.So you give him the pretty rune given to you by a god literally not twenty seconds earlier, and fight your way through soldiers to reach Antanas only to find out he's turned into a Rhogar himself! (dun dun.... dun.....). So you kill him, and the game is over.Congratulations."
