,Recommended,265300,31798830,Posted: 16 May,all,The Doom Slayer,"Been meaning to write this review for awhile as I feel the moniker of ""Souls like"" is a detriment to this game. Yes, it is Souls like, but it is NOT Dark Souls. Do not expect it to be just a copy of Dark Souls. Too many people bash on this game because it isn't Dark Souls. The combat is not as fast paced, opting for a more ""realistic"" approach. Every action you take has real weight behind it, you can't just swing your sword around and expect it to work out. It is a more methodical experience. If you go into the game with that in mind you should enjoy it just fine. The only real negative things I have to say about the game are that the level design is too linear with shortcuts that make no sense and the characters aren't all the interesting."
,Not Recommended,265300,28555627,"Posted: 23 December, 2016",all,latterman,"Lords Of The Fallen is a soulslike game set in a dark fantasy universe very similar to the one seen in Warhammer. Sounds good on paper, however I can't really recommend this game. Let's start with what's good.PROS:- Beautiful art style, lots of interesting details in the environment and in the gear.- Decent graphics with volumetric lighting. Sometimes the picture on the screen gets borderline gorgeous with all the ashes and sparks from hits flying around. Breathtaking.- Good combat system. Similar to the one seen in Dark Souls, yet with it's own twist (the addition of the Gauntlet is a nice touch). I love the timing-based combos — no more angry button smashing, you have to be careful with when you attack.- The Sound in this game is fantastic. Love the clenching of metal and heavy footsteps of the character.CONS:- Good God, camera gets atrocious sometimes. You're supposed to fight mobs, instead you're fighting game's camera.- Some mobs and bosses auto-aim on you. Meaning that while you're dodging their attack - they will follow you.- Speaking of Bosses. What was that? They all look the same! And why are they so easy? Beating the final boss in my second try is not good.- Story? What story? That plot-twist was borderline ludacris.- Mundane voice acting- Game's world navigation is frustrating. I've been cycling some areas over and over again, just because a narrow path was hidden between two bigger objects. Not really a good design decision. I personally think this happened because the image lacks depth.- Speaking of Game's World. It's really small. Loading screens between some areas are extremely frustrating and why are they there anyway? Damn.- There's only, like, 10 variations of enemies.- Game finale doesn't feel satisfying at all.- While Risk-Rewarding Check Point system is a great idea, there's really no risk to it. You can put all of your experience points into stats straight away without saving.All and all, this game is not hopelesly bad. It has lots of potential, yet somehow, at this moment, the developer didn't seem to push it hard enough. I can't recommend this game, however, I'll keep my ear to the ground for The Surge, see if Deck 13 will work on their mistakes."
