76561198061671546,Recommended,265300,22886829,"Posted: 9 May, 2016",all,Sciophyte,"Lords of the Fallen has a somewhat dented learning curve: unless you're a veteran of the Dark Souls franchise—which I'm told LotF emulates—you'll probably find the combat pretty challenging in the beginning, to say nothing of taking down the first boss or two. But once you develop certain magical skills, the difficulty drops almost to the point of tedium (for me, the skill that did it was ""Stab"" on a rogue, and to a certain extent, ""Shift""). Most common opponents suddenly pop like soap bubbles, and as soon as you learn to evade the most damaging boss attacks, the big guys no longer pose nearly as much of a threat as they're probably meant to do. And since the story is dark fantasy boilerplate with ciphers for characters, even the admittedly gorgeous visuals can no longer make up for the fact that your sole incentive for plodding through the game is the prospect of finding shinier toys in the next chest. That ain't much. I'm by no means saying LotF is a bad game, especially if you can get it during a sale, which is why I'm still recommending it. You may well get a few hours worth of fun out of this title. Just not enough fun—or challenge—to last to the very end of it."
