76561198000698735,Recommended,265300,32690722,Posted: 23 June,all,Last Knight Down,"Not sure why all the hate for this game; I'm a DS1 fanatic and I really don't care that they used some of the Souls formula to make this game enjoyable. Emulation is the truest form of flattery; And this game has plenty to offer in terms of it's own flair and fun. The environments and special effects are really pretty. (Not optimized the best, but oh well. I'm sure there are tweaks and mods out there to help with that. Usually it runs pretty well.) The game itself plays more like a Warhammer or Gears of War type of game, where you have a lot of big bodies and have to deal a lot of damage and tank a lot of hits. The aesthetic is also very similar; It has a lot of bloom, lens flare, particle effects, slo-mo and camera shake. It feels good to play and it's got pretty decent bosses, power climb and story dialogue. Some of the lines and voice acting are hit-or-miss, but the main character's voice acting is really strong. Travel through the game is pretty linear, but there are areas where lots of paths open up at the same time. You can't sequence break the whole game, which is probably for the best; However, you can get to a boss or some loot early here and there, which feels really good. There is a lot of loot to get and most of the weapons and armor in the game feel like they are there for a reason, having their advantages and disadvantages. There are also lots of legitimately mysterious things like secret paths, gates, chests and items you'll have to figure out how to get to or come back for later, like older adventure games. The game rewards grinding with an experience modifier that climbs as you defeat enemies, so the better you get the less time you will spend grinding, especially on additional playthroughs. There's even an unlock for the other spell trees and unique items you can get for playing through new game plus. The artwork and models in the game are also really impressive. I've finished it and I can't really find anything not to like about it, besides maybe not having a customizable equipment loadout system. This is a gem the internet rejected, and if you let the negative buzz deter you, you'll only be missing out. Give LotF a go, it's a good time."
