76561198065817797,Recommended,265300,32679294,Posted: 23 June,all,eyalpatihi,good and sort gameits like Darksouls but less hoursits wotrh the money when its on a discount
,Recommended,265300,12694244,"Posted: 30 October, 2014",all,GodEmperor,"In Short:Game is fun for the most part. The combat takes some getting used to because it is far more sluggish/slow than those who are used to the souls series. It's a pretty neat looking ascetic overall in my opinion, but the high fantasy style that seems similar to World of Warcraft, Diablo 3, or Darksiders series is getting a bit over used. The story is nothing special, but not bad either. There's a lot of lore to find, but it's told to you in scrolls and cutscenes and such, not like the Souls series where you find items and piece the lore together yourself.There are some nit picking problems like I don't find the jump mechanic and various areas to get some loot and require a jump any fun, just frustrating, but those small issues don't detract enough from the game's over all joy. The only big problem are the crashes. As of October 30th, the game crashes way too easily and often. For those who don't have an Nvidia to do that ""fix"" (which doesn't work for everyone) you're pretty much screwed until they patch it. The other issue is the frame drops which are fairly frequent (doesn't seem optimized). I'd wholly recommend it immediately if not for the crashes and frame drops. For now, I'd say get it if you're REALLY looking for a mixture of Diablo 3/Darksiders style world and Souls style combat, but I'd hold off until they finally fix these technical problems with the game.Steam seriously needs a third option for ""Do you recommend this game"" imo, basically ""Yes, with warnings"" or something.A Bit More Depth:Bosses (far as I can tell so far after playing as long as I have) aren't anything special. They're about on par with Dark Souls 2 in terms of design (which means it falls short, imo, to Demons's and Dark Souls bosses), but they are fun fights. A bit too many humanoid enemies which is disappointing, but the different humanoid types are vastly different in attack styles and require different ways to deal with which is fun. The settings for most bosses also are pretty Dark Souls 2 from my experience, plenty of room to maneuver (nothing so far that feels like Capra demon in DkS1 where you're cramped for room to move). I'd say the only real gripe here is that some bosses have some one shot killing abilities that you won't know how to deal with immediately and that can be frustrating, but I personally don't mind it too much if there are some good cues (without being blatantly told) of how to deal with it and most do have that, some are just more subtle than others.Another really cool thing about bosses is that they have the ability to get special loot from them when you beat them in a certain way. The only downside here is that there's NOTHING to indicate what that special way would be leaving you to have to look it up online or just stumble upon the solution by dumb luck (which means you might not know exactly what caused you to get the special loot).The level design is pretty straightforward as you go through the game (not much in terms of choice of path), but when you get through the game you open up more and more paths that show how there's some interconnectivity to the overall world design. For those who loved that aspect in Dark Souls, they'll enjoy it here as they get through toward later parts of the game. It's just a bit of a pity there's no real choice in path from the start in which way to go, but it's not bad from a story telling perspective and the levels look nice enough and have a good amount of interconnectivity within themselves for side paths and short cuts and such that it's never a bother (at least to me, you might feel differently).It's a bit sad you can't customize a look for your character, but that's to be expected given how they tell the story, but what is nice is how much you can customize your character in terms of armor and weapons to use. And the fact you always carry them all on you at once makes it easy to switch weapons and gear and find what you really enjoy. While it doesn't get as punishing as a Souls game because there is a pause menu that allows you to change gear, even in combat (to a degree, not at all points, but if you haven't been attacked or not attacking for a bit, you can switch comfortably as the game is paused to let you do so), it does allow such experimentation with the different weapons that you'll appreciate it as every weapon is VERY different from one another in every way and some will adhere to a person's playstyle more than others.For example: I started as a warrior, I used a sword and shield from the start and found I wasn't enjoying it as I did with Dark our Demons's Souls. The attack felt a bit too sluggish to capitalize on brief moments of an enemy's vulnerability and even though the shield claimed 100% defense, some enemies still seemed to attack through it (at a lesser damage than if I wasn't blocking) at points (far as I can gather that's more due to their attacks being able to pierce shields, so it's by design). So I have currently gone to using a larger two handed weapon that can do ridiculous damage and/or stun/stagger the majority of enemies to get through the game. I'll only occasionally use the shield for some attacks or in clutch moments. It's still very enjoyable though.To go on more about weapons, they are also upgradable by various ""runes"" you can find in the world and from enemies and have to unlock at an NPC and place within a weapon at that NPC (who can be summoned at specific parts of the world). The weapons and armor generally have 'sockets' to place these runes. So in that case, it's very WoW/Diablo 3 in the customization of weapons and less the way Dark Souls did it. The only downside is that Runes are ""unlocked' and what you get is random. You can use some Experience points to increase the chance for higher quality runes, but that randomness is still something I don't wholly like, but that's a personal opinion.Speaking of Experience points, they are very similar to Souls in the Souls games. They are your everything. You use it to unlock your magical abilities and they are used to unlock runes and they are used to gain points to be placed into specific attributes. In this way, it's a lot like the Souls games which I like. The more you spend into the points the higher the cost it is to get the point to spend for your attributes. The attributes are Strength, Vitality, Endurance, Faith, Luck, and Agility. For the most part, what each does is straight forward. Strength increases damage for larger weapons (and some small increases to equip burden), Vitality increases your HP s you can take more hits, Endurance is your energy/stamina (as well as equip burden), Faith is your magic/mp, Luck increases drop rates, and Agility is increased damage for smaller weapons and I think also equip burden, but I can't remember (haven't done anything with Agility yet). You can place points freely.You'll also need to spend experience points to get points to put into magic. Magics come in 3 types. Brawling, Deception, and Solace. You choose one at the start of the game and can't use the others at all for your first play through (I've read and heard that in NG+ you unlock a second tree and in NG++ you unlock the final tree). To go into each tree will be a bit too long with the characters I have left, but they are fairly unique from one another, but you'll never have a magic only character like in the Souls games.All in all, the game is fun and has some nice adjustments to the Souls systems (like the timing/combo system or the 'blood pools' that contains your expedience on death being able to heal you if you stay near it, but draining the experience in it, etc), but is not at all like the Souls in its overall presentation. It's a good game that's only really marred by the crippling frame rates at points and the endless crashes."
,Recommended,265300,13127826,"Posted: 28 November, 2014",all,Pump Action Poodle,"Okay. In order to truly get a good idea on what Lords of the Fallen is like, we need to look to a game called ""Dark Souls"" to explain it's gameplay. LotF sets out to be difficult from the get go, forcing the player into positions where patience is rewarded over arrogance. This would be decent enough, if not for the severe lack of content, or seeming lack of it. The game seems to suffer from a major pacing issue, and atmosphere issue, that Dark Souls does not. While Lords takes a lot of it's inspiration from the Souls series, from it's combat, to it's attempt (but ultimate failure) at recreating the frustratingly hard difficulty level of Souls, to it's story; it doesn't bring the atmosphere of severe hopelessness, and the feeling of just barely being able to trudge along into the next area of the game. The Warrior is capable of tanking so many blows it's just way too easy, the Cleric does way too much damage right out of the gate, and the Rogue is way too quick for his own good.That being said, the game is fun, it's just not what you've probably heard. It's easier than Dark Souls, way more forgiving, in a world that is attempting to recreate a hopeless environment and ultimately fails, making you feel like a total ♥♥♥♥ing badass instead of a total ♥♥♥♥ing pushover, but it's fun. I'll recommend it to anyone who enjoys their time with RPGs.For a number? How about 7/10. Solid, but could easily improve."
