,Recommended,265300,30465879,Posted: 12 March,all,nandasithu,"A lot of negative reviews come from frustration of players. This is true in this game. You die a lot, more so than compared to Dark Souls. Yes the comparison is always there, but this game has its unique points to differentiate from Souls and Bloodborn series. First of, Lords of the Fallen has solid and somewhat compact storyline. Second, the map itself is not that big after you finish your first playthrough. Lastly, this is more of a story driven RPG game, you will be appreciated at the end with the choices you made throughout the game.Now on the bad points of the game, the camera system is frustrating. I don't know how many times I've died just because I cannot face to the enemy or my character somehow facing the wall while wildly swing sword. This happens mostly in narrow corridor and dungeon, so most open area fights are no problem. Next on the voice acting. For a story driven game, I would expect some form of good voice acting. But alas, the main character voice is so dry, I don't know if he is speaking just making grunts. Lastly, the game punishes you for choosing speed focus characters. If you are planning to play Rouge and sneak up enemy from behind, just forget about it. The game wants you to be heavy fat guy with shield on and walk slowly like obese person.Overall, this game is not perfect but don't expect to be like Souls series or Bloodborn. Don't expect RPG like Skyrim or Dragon Age either. This game is really for niche audiences. Most will definitely hate it coz you die in the first two fights of the game. Just like Dark Souls series, if you look past all these negative points, at the end the experience is rewarding and I, myself enjoyed it. But this is not the game that I will come back to replay from time to time."
