,Recommended,265300,14632967,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,IronCross2160,"*In Progress Review*Lords of the Fallen, so far, has provided me with a more accessible version of Dark Soul's famously hard gameplay.  To be fair to each game, I will try to keep comparisons to a minimum, and to judge the game by its own merits and issues.To be concise I will divide this review into two sections.  Let me begin with things I enjoy about it:- Lords does do one or two things that, personally, I think they did better than Dark Souls.  The enemy AI is more varied and a bit more defensive.  Their move sets tend to control your character's motions and mechanics, as opposed to just hurting you.- I like the setting of Lords of the Fallen.  Post-apocalyptic fantasy is one of my favorites, as it's a combination of two genres I really enjoy.- Lords also is a very pretty game, I really like the design and aesthetics of it.  Mostly since I enjoy gothic stylings in my games, and Lords delivers that much in spades.  From Harkyn's armor, to the enemy designs, to the locales; all of it just drips dark fantasy.- Lords is challenging without being too challenging, you won't die as much in Lords as you would in a Dark Souls.  If you keep getting killed generally it means you just should not be wherever you are yet.  The game is gated by ""Meat Walls"" as opposed to obstructions, for instance locked doors.  Though those do occur as well.- Lords has an incredible inertia to the combat.  The weapons feel hefty, the strikes of the enemies feel powerful.  At times Lords is on-point with the combat, and you feel awesome about the results of an encounter.  The timing-based nature of combat is also a welcome adition.Now to things I'm not as fond of:- Lords needs a bit of polish, especially in just fine tuning the combat.  Occasionally you'll have a strike that should have hit, but did not.  This is just a minor sort of thing, and doesn't detract too much from the overall experience.- The lore in Lords is very flimsy.  Its there, and what's there is good, it just doesn't feel like there is enough of it.  The world is more sketched out than fleshed out.  However; the story is serviceable, and is good compared to a wide berth of games.- It seems that the Strength build is the most viable one, or at least the most easily accessible.  I'm about halfway through on a Strength run, and I dipped my toes in as a Dexterity build.  It didn't seem to be as effective.  However; I will not say any absolutes on this point, since I plan on going through the game again with a different build to test it out.Overall I recommend this game if Dark Souls caught your interest, but you can't get past the difficulty.  However; after playing through this, I recommend you give Dark Souls a try as well."
