,Recommended,265300,12840024,"Posted: 7 November, 2014",all,DeadTomGC,"No, it's not as good as dark souls... But the reason you are here is because you like Dark Souls combat and progression.This implements something similar to Dark Souls 1's combat and progression system, but personally, I think they've actually done a better job with it.Also, I think the bosses I've encountered so far have been brilliantly designed.  They don't look interesting at first glance, but actually fighting each one takes a completely unique stratagy that you have to figure out as you go, which is really quite satisfying.So, if that is all you want, get it.HOWEVER, if you want the rish story and varied vistas of darksouls... well you're not going to get it.IMPORTANT NOTE: While you may be able to run this game at max settings using your current CPU and GPU, I'd take a look at your RAM.  This game eats up a lot of it.  I recommend 16GB for max settings and 8GB for min to avoid thrashing.  At 8GB on max graphics, it was clear my CPU and GPU were fine, but every now and then It would freeze for a bit.  which indicated that something was being transfered to/from the disk.  After checking the the tsk manager, I found that I was using nearly 7GB of the 8 on my computer.  Since then I have upgraded my RAM to 16GB, and it runs at a smooth 60fps now.The level design is pretty good, and IMO is better than Dark Souls 2's level design. However, level design is not the same as the visual design.  Some people don't like the visual design since there isn't a ton of definition, but I think it's fine that way.  It just means you can't play with your eye's closed. Overall, that is pretty much the theme of the game.  Stay alert."
