,Recommended,265300,20140369,"Posted: 30 December, 2015",all,[SpS|GM]Mardan-CrunchyInTheory,"Lords of the Fallen is an Action RPG much like Dark Souls and Demon's Souls. In fact, you could probably draw more similaries with Dark Souls II rather than with Dark Souls I if you've played those games, just because of how the combat feels. It definitely has a clunkier feel than Souls does, but that works for this game because of the way the bosses, enemies, weapons, and shields are designed. The game has a much more 'character driven' feel to it due to the importance of your choices in dialogue, and the voice acted main character whose name and appearance you cannot change.Harkyn, your character, was imprisoned for his heinous crimes, but was freed when the demonic Rhogar Lords began invading this realm. Your job is to put an end to their tyranny, and you are the only one who can do it.- Pros -The combat feels great. You are encouraged to use your shield more in Lords than in Souls, because most of the time you are unable to 'roll through' attacks in the same way.Graphics are amazing. By far better looking than Souls in every way. From the lighting to the shadows to the shaders to the textures this game looks great. The animations and cloth physics, however, stand out far above the rest as true beacons of this game's beauty.Design is definitely different than the Souls games, but that's a good thing. Bosses have (mostly) unique-feeling designs and the environments look gorgeous. The weapons and armor have that really humongous-yet-complex look that fits perfectly with Harkyn and the game in general.Level Design is very good. I thought it was really interesting how the game had you backtrack through levels but using a different route and to a different destination that was unavailable before.I loved how the game ended. Seeing a culmination of your choices like that rather than ""walk toward or away from the bonfire"" was really nice and made me want to see what happened differently in NG+.The game lets you save at a checkpoint without activating the checkpoint's in-game effects. Please, Dark Souls III, feature this.Each of the bosses has a unique challenge (for instance, don't knock over any of the barrels used for a boss's special attack) that, if completed, gives you a unique version of the weapon it would normally drop.- Neutral -Weapon movesets may feel odd at times; he doesn't hold the greatswords, for example, the way you'd expect him to.I couldn't get the running shield bash to work half the time. I started running and he would put down the shield. Odd.Armor doesn't seem to be balanced very well. When Light Armor weighs more and defends more than the factory new Heavy Armor you just found, you know something's amiss.You can't reallocate your skill points.The UI can be hard to learn in the beginning, especially equipping new spells.The game had minor issues before I performed some fixes. I installed Legacy PhysX drivers, disabled Vsync and enabled frame rate cap, and ran the game in Fullscreen and it worked perfectly after that.The save points don't reset the enemies in the area. There is, however, a timer that prevents you from having infinite health and potions just from visiting a checkpoint.- The Cons -The DLC is absolutely horrid. Don't waste your money on it.The cutscenes can be awkward. It seems as though the animations for dialogue were done by a different person than the one responsible for the combat anims. Characters will fling their limbs about when expressing very mild emotions, and the voice acting isn't fantastic either. Kaslo's, in particular, voice sounds really forced and phoned-in.It's easy. I hardly ever died to enemies after I got decent weapons and armor. The reason I'm making this a con is that the bosses can be oddly challenging in comparison, and I was frankly expecting harder enemies from a Soulslike.Customization is not great. The game really wants you to be 'Harkyn'. I can't be 'Mardan the Warrior-Mage' like I can in Dark Souls II, wearing Medium armor and wielding a staff, a shield and a greatsword but still rolling around like an excited child. No, you are going to be an armored tank in Lords. It's hard for me to fear smaller enemies when literally every square inch of myself is covered with steel plate. Even the 'rogue' class doesn't feel very light. Rolling feels horrible, and I'd reccomend that you just roll (pardon the pun) with the heavy shield playstyle. There are four spells per class, and you can't change your class after character creation.Sometimes there's a general lack of direction on where to go. This is good, because it challenges you to think of the right path, eeexcept when the only direction is the name of an area you've never heard before in the game.Lack of NPCs. Seriously, there are like 5.Lack of thorough character development. Most of the characters are just generic 'military guy' or 'Yoda' or 'adventurous spunky character'- Final Verdict -Overall, Lords of the Fallen is a great nod to the famous Souls series and is fantastic at differentiating itself enough to not be a 'clone'. It has very high production value, its combat is satisfying, its graphics are utterly beautiful, but its variety is offputting. You'll find yourself fighting similar enemies over and over in several different beautifully-rendered environments. You'll find powerful new weapons through the interesting loot system, and upgrade them with stat-boosting runes. The story will intrigue you, and the ending will make you wonder about what could have been.Should you buy it? If you liked the Souls games, or just want to try this one, then yes, buy it. It's a steal on sale at 80% off, which is when I picked it up. The DLC, however, is a different matter entirely.I'm taking a whole point off because of the lack of enemy variety. It really is distracting toward the end, and takes away a lot of the challenge and unique feeling of the different areas. Imagine if Dark Souls's Lost Izalith had regular hollows in it.Final Verdict: 7.5/10 - Greathttp://store.steampowered.com/app/265300/"
76561198004096601,Recommended,265300,20156310,"Posted: 31 December, 2015",all,Offline,"Good:If you play it not expecting Dark Souls, you will have a good time.This game is better than most games out there but sadly in my opinion it had a rough launch and got a somewhat bad reputation from the get go.I bought this game expecting a buggy mess with pretty graphics but with a few hours of playtime. I can honestly say, even after spending many, many hours with the Souls games that, this game is different, rich in weapons and content and fun to play. It is so satisfying to hit things in this game. The multiplier (not multiplayer, this game is strictly singleplayer)- system is a great addition where you can go back to previous areas ang kill weaker enemies to increase your multiplier, and then go and earn some major exp.Sure, the enemies and the locations can get a LITTLE repetetive but no where close to what people are saying, I mean the detailed enviornments are incredible and well layed out. It FEELS like you are making progress and it is FUN.It is not Dark Souls, it does not even come close to that complexity, but it does not fall flat on it's face.The enemy A.I is good and it manages to surprise you. The same goes for the Bosses. Some bosses are harder than those in Dark Souls... I do not know if this game intended this or if it is a result of poor balancing but you can get DESTROYED in a few areas, which is good.There are so many weapons and Armours, and granted you will not use them all, they are there to play around with.The rune system to imbue your gear is good and simple and gives you a reason to grind some enemies, if you like grinding that is.Bad:The lore is forgettable and not really interesting at all, but luckily you can totally bypass it. It would have been better to not have ANY lore, then there might have been a mystery to solve but for some reason they went with a lackluster story.There are a few bugs I have noticed, with closed doors looking like they are open and one crash when switching weapons. I have also heard that there might be a game breaking bug after fighting the second boss but I have not noticed it.The new game system is kind of a gray zone for me. You can not play with the same character past NG++. It is not unlimited like Dark Souls.TLDR:The combat is satisfying and you can choose to play in whatever way you want. There are not many spells but you can use them all. Level up, get stronger, progress. Forget the story and just kill stuff in a very, very pretty world. It is hard enough and the bosses are rewarding. Everything is so BUFF AND COOL AND AWESOME LOOKING OMG. Really good artists. This is one of those hidden gems, plagued with a few issues and a bad reputation, but if you can see past it, you might just love it."
