,Recommended,265300,20461060,"Posted: 10 January, 2016",all,chadamas,"I don't write a lot of reviews, but it seems criminal to me that Lords of the Fallen's current Steam average is ""Mixed,"" so I'm doing my small part to tip the scales. This game isn't perfect, but it's a lot of fun and I highly recommend it if you can catch it on sale (I bought it for $9.99).GraphicsMy PC isn't top-of-the-line by today's standards, but I was able to keep visual settings pretty high and maintain a solid framerate. The environments are beautiful, your character looks like a total badass no matter what weapon or armor combination you equip, the common enemies are well-designed and intimidating enough, the Lords are terrifying, and the animations are smooth. There was never a moment in-game where I was disappointed in the visuals, but I guess if I'm digging for a ""con"" here, I'd say that there wasn't a huge variety in the environments.SoundSometimes, music and sound effects can make or break a game experience for me, but this wasn't one of those times. The theme song is great and there were a couple of times when the music crescendoed while I was fighting a Lord (which was cool and added to the ""badass"" factor), but for the most part, I didn't notice the music at all in this game. That's okay, I guess. The sound effects were impressive, especially the growls and roars of enemies and the impacts of weapons against shields and walls. The one thing I really wished as I was playing through the game was that enemy footsteps were more audible. There are times when you find yourself navigating corridors where enemies are patrolling, and you should be able to hear that big dude with the axe stomping around just down the hall...but you can't.The voice acting was well-performed throughout the game. Some were better than others, but for the most part, these people did a good job (the most cringeworthy line in the whole game is probably Harkyn's ""My vow of defiance!"" in the opening sequence).StoryOkay, to be fair, the story isn't what will draw you into this particular game, but it is well-crafted, and so many minor details are revealed through picking up scrolls, which activate voiceovers that describe enemies, experiences, or locations. Even if you don't find yourself caring about the lore, you learn more and more through the words of characters that you haven't even met...and this is often a rewarding experience. You learn more about this world and its history if you care to, but it feels more alive, regardless. There were people here before you, and you get to hear their stories and connect the pieces for yourself.GameplayThis is it. This is why you start the game, and this is why you continue it...even after you've been killed 30+ times by the same enemy and you curse so loudly that you wake up your wife and fear for your marriage. The gameplay is just. So. GOOD. Okay, okay, with the boss fights, it sometimes feels less like you're exploiting weaknesses and more like you're just memorizing patterns, but for some inexplicable reason, it's still fun. Blocking, dodging, rolling, slashing, thrusting--it all feels so...right. Now, granted, it takes a while to get there, and it takes even longer if you're experimenting with different weapon types, but once you get the hang of it, this combat experience is beautiful.My first piece of advice: don't just spam your attack buttons. This took me a while to figure out, but each weapon type has a narrow interval after each swing (slash, thrust, etc.) when you should activate your next attack for a quicker follow-up, with less of an impact on your energy. You can even practice this without enemies around--just try out different combinations and watch your energy bar. It will flash with each perfectly-timed attack.Also keep an eye on your equipment and Endurance. If your Weight score is green, you'll move and execute combinations more quickly (this may be less important for warriors wearing heavy armors and shields, but I played primarily with short swords and daggers, so speed was extremely important).You have quite a few customization options as far as character development and equipment, but you need to keep a few things in mind. This is a combat RPG with astrongemphasis on melee combat. Your ranged attacks are limited to spells and your gauntlet, which also uses up your magic. In general, you won't be fighting or killing enemies from a distance. You also won't be collecting tons of loot and trading/selling items. It's just not that type of game. Personally, I was okay with that...lately, when I've played some other RPGs, I've hoped that the enemy I just killed didn't drop anything, because it felt more like work than play to be constantly managing my inventory.  There are runes that you can equip to weapons and armor, and there are attributes that you can improve as you progress, but this is not nearly as involved as, say, Skyrim or Diablo or even Borderlands.SummaryTo sum things up: Lords of the Fallen is an excellent combat RPG. Just know what you're getting before you get it. You'll die (probably a lot), but the combat is amazing, and you'll feel a sense of accomplishment with each enemy that you defeat."
,Recommended,265300,13707031,"Posted: 29 December, 2014",all,Makro,"I'm just going to be open right here - I LOVE this game.I've just beaten it for the first time and I'm going to beat it agaIn and then again in NG+ and NG++.So what's so good about it?Well, a lot of people compare it to Dark Souls. And in some ways it's similar. It does have the same weighty combat system, where you have to commit to each and every one of your attacks, that have lengthy animations and can not be interrupted mid-swing by the player; hits received, however, will stop your attack. You need to know the attack patterns of all enemies you encounter to survive in the first half of the game, looking for opportunities to strike without losing precious HP.HP in this game can be restored in 3 ways - by a trinket called Life Leech that I personally only got in the later part of the game, that gives you HP for every monster you kill; by casting a Prayer spell, that acts as a decoy for your enemies and also regenerates a little bit of your health; and, most efficiently, by drinking health potions. Your supply of potions is limited and can only be restored by using a Shard - a checkpoint, essentially - or by dying.This works really well with another system in place - the XP modifier. The more monsters you kill without using a checkpoint or dying, the more XP you get for each consequent kill, up to 2.0 times more XP for kill. This is very handy, but forces you to refrain from healing and restocking at checkpoints for longer and longer. The game's progress still can be saved at a checkpoint without losing the modifier, but that will not restock your potions and health. It is also said that the more XP you have ""banked"" - kept unspent with a risk of losing it - the better loot you can get.This all makes for a thrilling experience, where your stakes are high, and combat feels important, as every monster you meet has a good chance of killing you.That said, the feeling only lasts throughtout the first half of the game.Unfortunately, as you grow stronger, especially if you min-max the♥♥♥♥♥♥out of your character the way I did it, the fights get easier and easier. In the beginning bossfights took tries and tries to win, and even ordinary monsters had me respawning time after time. By the time I entered the Rhogar Realm for the first time, after, apparently before my time, killing the Rhogar Lord the Champion (I've killed him 4th, later discovering that he should've been the 5th boss to die), I felt immensely powerful. I still could be killed, don't get me wrong, and I died quite a few times when I goofed up, but most of the fights came to ""Bash-Leap-Dodge-Repeat"", with some enemies often dying from one heavy attack after being bashed in the face with a Tower Shield.Boss fights, while each having their own mechanics and even bonus difficulty conditions rewarded with special loot, got easier. 5th and 6th bosses I've met I've killed in 2 minutes and 50 seconds respectively. Last two bosses took me two tries each, in contrast with the 3rd boss that took 6.The game also feels short. It took me 14 hours to beat it for the first time, and the ending certainly feels a bit abrupt, and not much is explained to you, definitely setting the players up for a sequel.Overall, Lords of the Fallen has very solid mechanics, absolitely GORGEOUS look to it, wonderful aesthetic and atmosphere, but feels like the developers ran out of steam in the second half of the game, quickly wrapping it up with whatever good ideas they still had. It's a great experience, yet short, and it definitely could use some more difficulty in the end."
76561198092407538,Recommended,265300,15605679,"Posted: 28 April, 2015",all,Boogalou18,"I decided not to review this game until after I beat it.And after beating it, I can say that I really enjoyed this game. It is ""soulsy"" but it has enough differences in design and gameplay that its not a simple copy. The magic in particular feels a lot different. Since it acts mainly as a secondary combat choice, it never forces you to go full caster. The level design is also different, it feels really full and there are a lot more open spaces than in dark souls, but it is definitely smaller, and you can tell. There is no real late game areas, the mobs just get replaced with harder versions. The boss fights were all pretty fun and have cool sub challenges within them. The boss variety does leave something to be desired. Almost all the fights are in some sort of arena. The combat is actually really fun. A lot of people call it clunky but I just think its heavier. Everything just seems to hit harder, you included. For me though its the weapons and armor that really shine. There are a lot of sets and weapons for this size of game and every weapon you get usually is useful at the time you get it. All in all if you like the souls series or just like combat oriented rpgs you should check this out. 75/100ps. a lot of the performance issues and crashes have gotten better, not perfect...better."
