,Not Recommended,265300,13578872,"Posted: 24 December, 2014",all,Nawfiz,"LOTF is the first of a new genre called Souls-like, and it's doing an okay job at it. There are some stupid mechanics that shouldn't be in a game that follows in the foodsteps of a legend like Dark Souls. There seems to be only one solution to whatever problem you might encounter, and it gets quite boring after a while.The best example I have is (spoilers!) the champion boss which does a charging attack where you have to either have a tower shield to cower behind or do a shield bash with a medium shield. This will result in you stunning the boss and you'll get a few hits in, then it's back to baiting out the charge attack. It gets old real quick.All in all, LOTF has plenty of good things going and if future games learn from this game, they'll do great. LOTF, however, did not do that great and I don't recommend it."
,Not Recommended,265300,14077095,"Posted: 19 January, 2015",all,The Colgate King,"How do I describe this game?  It is a horribly made game.  I know several people have called it a ""hidden gem"" or ""dark souls lite"" but I would suggest you play dark souls instead.  Lets start off with a break down of pros and cons.Pros1.  Graphically better for the most part2.  Sound is better3.  It has voice acting and tries to flesh out its story more directly than a souls game.4.  Linear for the most part, save for a few areas it is hard to get lost.  You just keep going forward and you will eventually find your way through most roadblocks.Cons1.  Uninspired enviornments.  You will spend most of your time trudging through dark areas or fiery areas.  Do not expect vibrant areas with variety.  You are either in castles, caves, or some mixture of the two.2.  Very glitchy.  I have seen enemies scale invisible ladders and get stuck in the sky box only to be unattackable save for magic.  This might not have been a problem if I went full magic, but using the warrior archtype I had to use one or two spells then wait for magic to regenerate.3.  The magic feels underwhelming.  I did go melee but I had a decent amount of faith, my magic however depleted far faster than I feel it should have to be effective.  This may be due to an armor penalty but I noticed no difference in magic consumption between heavy and medium armors.4.  Magic/Skills feel uninspired in this game, like they were tacked on as an afterthought.  Some skills felt outright useless and others felt like they were completely overpowered.  As a warrior I could pop rage and just power through most boss fights in one or two uses.5.  Enemy AI is terrible.  Souls games aren't known for great AI, but they are HAL 9000 whem compared to LotF AI.  Boss attacks are far to easy to bait out with encounters and offer very little in the way of challenge.6.  When you get lost, you get lost hard.  While many areas you can just head forward, there are some places where you can find yourself walking around for hours trying to find out where to go simply because the game has a very poor progression funnel in certain areas (I am looking at you Annihilator).7.  Combat feels sluggish and can swing from boring to frustrating very quickly.  Once again I am viewing this from the warrior archtype, but two handed weapons have such a long wind up and awkward attack angles they feel like Harken is more of a flailing idiot than any skilled warrior.  Some enemies would stand there and take it while others would dance around or attack endlessly giving you little to no chance to recover or plan a counter attack.8.  The kick is useless.  It requires a huge amount of stamina and I have yet to see it be more efficient at breaking a turtling enemy than just spamming attack combos and smashing through them.9.  Exploding enemies.  Har har you have a booby trapped enemy that explodes on death.  Real cute and I could let that one slide, except these enemies are usually very powerful and there are far too many of them in the latter half of the game.  There is a specific mage type enemy that can deal horrendous ranged damage, put up a damage shield around him, drain your life, and has an annoyingly fast melee attack that will knock you down.  The blast radius of the explosion will result in you taking damage more often than not.10.  Main quests have a tracker and sub quests do not.  This is just annoying.  If you don't want a quest tracker fine, but don't go half way.  Either let us choose the quest to track or make us use a log.11.  Quest NPC's can just up sticks and leave.  This may be a glitch, but when I tried to turn in human skulls for a quest the quest giver just decided he had better things to do and went fishing or something, because he wasn't there when I arrived to turn in.12.  Rune upgrade system feels tacked on.  You can use runes to upgrade your equipment, but don't expect any major changes to your playstyle.  Some runes will provide enough of a benefit to give you notice, but most are borderline useless.13.  The game is just a slog.  Nearing the latter half of the game I just wanted it to be over.  Playing it felt more like a chore and less like entertainment.  The fighting was uninspired, there is very little enemy variety (plenty of reskins though).14.  The story is about a generic as you can get.  You can smell the plot twist coming from a mile away.  Some side elements have no effect on the story.  The ending is a carbon copy rip off of Fallout 3 where specific choices are recapped.15.  Damage scaling makes little to no sense.  I had a harder time fighting the lightly armored twin swordsman rogues than I did fighting mages or heavy knights.  My armor offered no defense against their all melee damage and they could begin an attack after my starting frame and stun me with a single hit before I was able to connect.  In the latter half of the game poise becomes a useless stat as any human enemy can stagger you with one strike.The game is exactly what it is trying to be, a cheaply made knock off of souls trying to cash in on its success.  They took out a lot of the components that made the Souls games fun and shoveled in AAA game concepts that just hobbled our outright broke the experience.  Stats and builds become more important than skill the further you get into the game.  With appropriate skill and planning I can do a SL1 4 kings run and become a darkwraith, but in this game I just don't see that being especially viable.  Doable?  Yes, but I doubt you would get any enjoyment out of it.  The armor looks nice but at the same time it appears ripped clean out of Warhammer without any editing (the trinket flags look suspiciously like the mark of Chaos).  If you want to experience this game just get a Souls game, you will save money and derive more enjoyment from it.  Souls is a better designed game, hands down, and while it may appear ""more difficult"" the difficulty feels less hamhanded.  LotF's difficulty doesn't feel rewarding, its just one slogfest after another.I haven't had buyer's remorse this bad since Brink"
