,Not Recommended,265300,19936756,"Posted: 25 December, 2015",all,Aaron,"Do NOT buy this game. I spent nearly 3 hours trying to fix this game just to get it to work.First, the game freezes at the numerous adverts before the title screen even appears. Something involving non-windowed mode and smaller resolutions can help with this.Second, if you can get around that, then the game goes to permanent black screen at the title screen and just plays music indefinitely. This is because there's no saved game available, so it won't continue.Third, if you did not alt+tab out of the game during the load up, the game will crash on loading the save file. In some cases, the opposite is true and that alt+tab will cause it to crash at title screen. It's pot luck.Fourth, if you've managed to get passed all of that (which I did not), the game will then crash at any opportunity it can. Boss fight? Crash. Cut scene? Crash. Turned around too fast? Crash. Did nothing but stood still waiting for a crash? Crash. All of this from countless horror stories online I stumbled across during my search for a fix.The real problem is that these bugs have apparently existed since at least 2014. The fact the developer has not fixed this at all is a major concern.Since it took so long to try to fix this game (and to no avail) I'm now outside of the refund time. I'm hoping that the support team will at least factor in the broken nature of the game, but I can't say yet. Don't make the same mistake I did.Edit: The support team refunded the game for me, so I at least have my money back now. Looks like it will go on Dark Souls II instead."
,Recommended,265300,13306843,"Posted: 10 December, 2014",all,M1 Garand Ping,"Lords of the Fallen is a gem of a punishing Action-RPG with alot of replayability and an interesting story with alot of discoverable groundwork for it's lore through audio-notes and hidden areas. Although many people have given this a negative review based on their issues with its stability, I can honestly and shamelessly tell you that I have played this game through twice with an Nvidia 660 Ti and I have NEVER experienced a crash once.It saddens me greatly that people flay the game with their issues running it instead of focusing on the gameplay itself. If someone is unable to run it smoothly it is acceptable and understandable to make its stability a major negative point, but I feel this drastically overshadows the game itself and its amount of negative reviews do NOT reflect its worth in my eyes.On to the review:PROs:-Easy to pick up and play, a challenging yet simple introduction to its genre. A game equally providing the footwork for Dark Souls-esque games to newcomers with a slightly more adaptable learning curve and a challenge for veterans of the genre such as players of Demon's Souls, Dark Souls and Dark Souls 2 (I have played all three).-Great story with titbits of collectable lore. The story is not over the top and hard to follow but is fairly involved if you choose to collect the audio-notes. It gives its players a choice to skip the notes and focus more on the gameplay, leaving the story more of a vanilla 'Knight-kills-monsters' type deal, which is fine too.-Smooth and responsive combat feel. The games core mechanics reflect your combat style through the gear you use and the weapons you wield, much like the Dark Souls series. If you wear light armor and use daggers, you will be alot more fragile but can potentially land a hit with each button press and have a light and nimble roll. If you wear the heaviest of attires, you will have a clunky roll and your hits will have more of a delay and wind-up to them, reflecting the feel of bearing such a burden, however, you can take alot more punishment before dropping and can hit like a truck. Play your way.CONs:-Voice acting and lip sync. Some of the dialogue between the essential NPCs feels almost forced. They play a preset animation loop whilst their dialogue plays over the top. Whilst this doesn't bother some players, such as myself, if you have a strict immersion policy this will be a bother, but is by no means game-breaking.-Noticeable difficulty drop-off point. After you've been playing for a while and grinding away with those big enchanted weapons and armors of yours, you will start to notice a point where things are dying a bit too quickly. This is mainly an issue if you choose a heavily armored, warrior-type class, where endlessly pouring your points into vitality and strength starts working a little TOO well. On my NG+ of my warrior, I was so big and angry that I only died once, and it was falling off a cliff... you get the point. Whilst this is much less of an issue with rogue-like characters, it should be pointed out. Furthermore, if you are looking for a challenge or are more accustomed to Dark Souls like me, you should definately go for a rogue, as it will provide consistent difficulty, even through your NG+.-Loot variation system. Whilst the game uses a system where you cannot get the same piece of loot twice, which is a brilliant idea, it simply does not have enough variation in it's gear to support it. All the weapons and armor scale with your attributes so you can potentially keep your favourite sword or helmet forever and all of the equipment is very well modelled and aesthetically pleasing. However, once you find a supreme piece of gear, you spend the rest of the game picking up pennies and belly button lint by comparison. For example, once I got my full 'Lords' set of heavy armor, even in NG+ I couldn't find anything that even came CLOSE to it in comparison, and I am a man who loves his loot.Conclusion:In short, I had ALOT of fun with this game and its a surefire candidate for my GOTY, I would recommend it to anyone looking for a fun and involved challenge without diving head first into the Souls series. It has alot of solid gameplay hours, beautiful environments and gear, an interesting and involved story and a very 'play-your-way' attitude.9/10"
