,Recommended,265300,34677718,Posted: 1 September,all,tfgleonel,"Lords of the Fallen is one of those games that are very underrated because it is too close to the original ones from where the devs took their inspiration to create this, and people tend to label those games just as a bad copy, a bad version of the original game. Which is the case most of the times, but not with Lords of the Fallen.First of all, there are some very clear differences between this game and the Souls series. Lords of the Fallen is more focused on its story and how to present it to the player than the Souls  games that are more focused on the world, difficulty, and how to beat the adversaries and situations, kind of leaving the details of the story ""hidden"". That is something that I enjoyed very much, because I am a player more of roleplay, story and exploration of the world and its characters than a fan of hack and slash. So I am more concerned of being part of that world than to conquer it. If you favour those things as well you are probably going to enjoy this game. It is not that the Souls series don't have good stories, far from that, but the story, the details, except for the main part, it is too ""concealed"". Take the complains about Lords of the Fallen: Most of them are about how bad people consider the combat to be. I disagree it is bad but I agree with the fact that there aren't many options..Second, everybody says that the Souls games are hard. I don't think this way. Perhaps because I am of a time when you had to go back all the way to the start of the game if you fail to beat it and that rarely happens nowadays. I think the Souls games demand time, patience, and practice, but it is not very much a matter of skill, except perhaps when facing another player, and that's where Lords of the Fallen stays far behind the original games, not having multiplayer options. But at least you won't explode in anger because you played 20 hours only to get an item from a Dual Skeleton Katana Dark Phantom or because no matter what you can't beat that part and you need to farm (and farm, and farm and keep farming) and improve before continuing the game. Without resorting to duplicating itens. Meaning: Lords of the Fallen  won't be a pain in the ♥♥♥♥♥ to solve something like any Souls games.Lords of the Fallen is considerable easier than any Souls game, but it does have an unbalanced difficulty: Everything is easy, except for the Worshipper boss and one or other situation. Plus the difficulty changes a lot depending on the class that you choose.Third the graphics and the concepts of the world: The Souls series have a nice concept that I prefer very much over the Lords of the Fallen. Both games are based on fantasy worlds, but the concepts for the Souls were more ""realist"" and dark, to stimulate and translate the atmosphere of the worlds of those games, this is true both to Demon Soul as well as to all of the Dark Souls and even to Bloodborne, while the concepts for the Lords of the Fallen are more exaggerated, sometimes even disproportional, everything is too huge, armors are huge, weapons are huge, the atmosphere is more colorful, etc.  Even the rules for carrying weight (for the inventory), don't really make much sense in this game. The weight of what you wear, of what is equipped, is counting, but the weight of any item that you carry in your inventory is completely ignored, so you can carry ten thousand weapons. But the way the character moves (and the creatures as well) are very nice, small movements are very fluid, people complain a lot about the speed of this game but it works for me; Harkyn does have his troubles dealing with heavy weapons, sometimes he can't even lift them unless you choose the two hands option. But he tries to lift them and fails. It is a nice touch. So, it is really nothing that bothers, after all it is just a game and that doesn't ruin the ""immersion"".One thing that kind of ruins the immersion, though, is the graphic. The graphic of Lords of The Fallen is very nice, all the details, the atmosphere, the character and creature designs, the landscapes, the change of tones and scenarios much more varied than on the Souls series... all of this are nice. The problem is that there are too many graphic issues. Dead enemies or broken props sometimes stays floating in the air. That bothers a little, but it is no big deal. The camera sometimes may be a problem too.The game has some other minor bugs and mistakes, sometimes you trespass an enemy instead of hitting it or vice versa, your skills are resetted and the game changes your class automatically (that actually only happened twice with me), some crashes, etc. But they are no big deal as well.So, all of the problems of the game are not really big issues, and despite being labeled as a copy, the good points are much more and far better than the bad points. In general, the atmosphere, graphics (when free of bugs), music and sound and especially and most important the rhythm of the game are all great.Final Considerations:If you don't know or if you are not an avid fan of any Demon or Dark Souls, you may like this game, despite the fact that it was inspired on those other games. Actually you are probably going to enjoy it even more because you won't be comparing all the time.The story is ok, the characters doesn't appear very much but they have some nice interactions, dialogues (simple but they work to show the world of the game and its story) and the most important thing about this game: it is very fun to play. You can play for many hours and forget the time."
