76561198148997598,Not Recommended,265300,21223312,"Posted: 14 February, 2016",all,The Iconoclast,"I wasn't looking for it to succeed Dark Souls, but I did expect it to at least be a satisfying experience in its own way. It's not and if I hadn't left it running idly while I did other things and accrued a play-time in excess of 2 hours, I'd have refunded this game even though I only paid $10 for it.The combat is painfully slow, the enemies/environs tiresomely monotonous and the controls as unresponsive as a vegetable.I knew the combat would be slow going in, but actually experiencing it is another matter entirely. Imagine the movement and mechanics of Dark Souls were universally reduced to half speed and suddenly the collision detection was off. So you have daggers moving like greatswords, axes moving like ultragreatswords that you don't have sufficient strength to wield, and anything bigger moving like glaciers across concrete. Top that with getting hit for 48 damage by the first boss even though every visible part of your character is half a foot away from his sword and you have combat in Lords of the Fallen. Why would you make everything slower instead of maintaining a wide and interesting variety of speeds? How could you fail to ensure that collision detection was working perfectly in a game where nothing else matters? These are the questions...The Steam screenshots cover the extent of enemy/environmental visual design. You have your spiky-pauldroned guy with winged helm and axe...then a spiky-pauldroned boss with winged helm and sword/shield combo who only 30 minutes later appears in miniature as a standard enemy...then there are some blorchy zombie-mutant whatsits and some spiky-armored hooded guys with swords. Yeah...Dark Souls did the boss as a standard enemy thing too...but the first time you see that is much later in the game and it gives you a tremendous sense of how far you've come. Seeing a boss as a standard enemy 30 minutes after you beat him gives you a tremendous sense of ""what the ♥♥♥♥ is this ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t"".As for aspects less mechanical...Many people said the voice acting was competent. I say that's at most partially true. I don't know if it's poor acting or poor writing or both...but I know for certain that the near comically exaggerated animations certainly didn't help. The exchange between the player character and the woman on the cusp of throwing some priest over a wall made me wish I was the priest and that she had followed through to completion.The music is generic and lame. The menus are barely serviceable. The different armors don't have any sense of uniqueness because their sizes all conform to the beefy frame of your character. The enemies continue to make annoying sounds 5 seconds after they're dead. Objects/textures sometimes appear to be clipping through each other. etc...etc...But none of this would matter at all if the game was fun to play. And that is Lords' cardinal sin."
