,Recommended,265300,20117896,"Posted: 30 December, 2015",all,fenrif,"I went into this not expecting much as people tend to dismiss this game out of hand. I was plesantly surprised.I'll say right off the bat that this is a Dark Souls 2 clone. I say two specifically because this feels much more similar to the sequel than the original (or Demons'). Nearly all your enemies are humanoids, for example.It plays a lot better than Dark Souls 2 though. No enemies pivoting on the spot mid swing to auto-track you, all the hitboxes seem tight and what you expect. Also it looks a shed load prettier for what that's worth.The conversation system is a bit pointless, and I was a bit dissapointed in the weapon upgrading system. You can slot gems into your gear for things like +4 dmg or +10 melee protection. But most weapons can only take 1 or 2 runes, so you never really feel like your changing anything dramatically. You won't get that Dark Souls feeling of taking a crappy starting weapon and upgrading it to +10. Though you can freely swap runes in and out as you wish so it's a bit more fluid.If you're looking for more Dark Souls then give this a shot. It's a straight up clone with a fresh coat of paint. In comparison to the other games like this I'd say this comes in somewhere inbetween Demons and DS2 in terms of quality.Worth a punt, especially if you see it on sale."
76561197980701922,Recommended,265300,20161406,"Posted: 31 December, 2015",all,BOATS,"So I feel safe reviewing this due to the fact that it's been about a year since my inital playthrough, and my opinion of it is unchanged.It's alright.My first playthrough was a lot of fun.  You'll go through the standard stuff of discovering new weapons, rerolling to use different stuff, and the inital thrills of exploring the areas.  Like everyone else has mentioned, the combat is very Souls-like.  It's a little more clunky and slower-paced, but that's not a bad thing.  The difficulty is pretty low; most of the boss fights are super gimmicky.  The story is bland and the dialog is atrocious, but it's not too invasive and does an okay job linking one area to the next.  I enjoyed exploring the world, trying out different weapons, modding them in different ways, and reaching the conclusion, but that's where the enjoyment stopped.  There's some replayability, different classes, different stats with different weapon sets, and a few different endings, but I felt no desire to go back through the game and find them.  I moved on with my life and came back across this game recently and decided to give it another shot with some fresh eyes.  The level design is a certain kind of bland, it's so unremarkable that the layout is memorable but not enjoyable.  After just about a full year of not playing it, I still didn't have much of a desire to go back through the game.I believe I got the game on sale, and I got a solid 15 hours of gameplay out of it that were very enjoyable.  I'm sure that's more than enough to justify whatever I spent on it.  I see that it's currently on sale (posting during the winter sale of 2015) for $9, and it's a phenomenal game for that price.  The base price of $49.99 seems a little steep.  If you don't have a habit of restarting when you find cool gear, you can probably get through it faster than I did.  If you're new to the action-rpg genre and struggle with the difficulty, it might take you 20ish hours for a full-explore playthrough.  Either way, the game is enjoyable, but quickly forgotten."
