76561198046188820,Recommended,265300,13527171,"Posted: 22 December, 2014",all,Khalel of Rivia,"OK first off, this game may have a few similarities with the Demon/Dark Souls series, mainly controls and the stamina/energy system, but that's where it ends.Lords of The Fallen is a great game. Graphics are stunning and even better if you make some small tweaks. If you are having problems making it look good for you then i suggest changing your GPU settings and have them override the ingame settings. I changed the settings in my Nvidia Control Panel to really make this game look amazing.With the controls being similar to DS/DSII you might start trying to play the same way but try not to because the combat in LotF is very different. It's nowhere near as difficult but it's much slower. You have to time your attacks carefully when there are openings to counter attack. That being said it's not too punishing if you mess up as long as you don't get sloppy. The combat can be very satisfying if you take your time.There are plenty of different weapon and armor types to choose from that directly affect your weight and encumberance to suit your play style. I prefer great axes myself in this game because when timed right your attacks are brutal and the ragdoll force looks awesome after a kill but not overdone. Hit boxes in general are very tight and realistic in my opinion.The story is ok. Nothing epic there. The problem is that it's very easy to lose focus on the reason the protagonist is there in the first place. ""Oh yea. I'm more than a demon-killing badass, there's something I'm supposed to do."" I found myself with this thought a few times after i would complete a part of the main quest and the story brought me back in. Other than that, it's fine. Voice acting, in my opinion, is very well done.The game world isn't as big as some other games in the genre. You'll find yourself going through some of the same areas to get to different objectives. Also there is no compass or radar or anything like that to give you a general idea of your location. You have to memorize the areas to get around more efficiently. I personally liked this, adding to the immersion for me, but i can see how this can be frustrating to some due to frequently getting lost or going in circles. Exploration is encouraged as there are plenty of secrets and lore to be found and even more after you complete your first playthrough, which adds to the replayability factor of Lords of the Fallen.Character development and growth is straight forward and easy to manage. Some rpg's can get a little extensive with their leveling system and attribute and/or skill distribution making for a lot of useless skills or abilities. Lords of the Fallen lets you level your character in different ways depending on your combat choice, warrior, rogue, or mage, all with useful and practical abilities that you will use all the time. You can allocate attribute points to your strength, vitality, faith etc. separately to raise the attributes you actually need and ignoring less needed ones for your play style.LotF does suffer from a few bugs. You can basically read about them all over the reviews for this game. I've seen a few glitches here and there but nothing game breaking. Mostly stuff like occasional frame rate drops or bodies glitching here and there. The only noticeable bug that i encountered was my graphics settings not saving while i was tweaking them when i first bought the game. But haven't ran into the issue again.Lords of the Fallen is a great third person action rpg that is visually breathtaking (after some tweaks) with a satisfying and rewarding combat system when patience is used and a story that can start becoming an afterthought after a few hours in but brings you back in at key points, overall it's pretty decent. The bugs are present but don't break immersion in my opinion. I really enjoyed it and hope for more like this from City Interactive."
76561198028290531,Recommended,265300,13824445,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,Tormented,"Lets get the important bit out of the way first.STAY AWAY IF YOU CAN'T TAKE TROUBLESHOOTING.Stability. Stability. Stability.It took me over 3 hours to get the game to load past the first cut scene. Turns out my problem was lack of virtual memory. Popped it up to 4Gigs and off I went with no crashes in sight. I've got 16 gigs of ram so I don't know WHY it NEEDED VM at all.This game is wonderful. It's immersive, powerful and rage inducing at times. (Beside the stability issues)Pros:-Beautiful world and armor choices-Heavy response based combat.  Each swing feels more realistic than Darksouls.-Full fantastic voice acting-Difficult but not too terribly mind numbingly painful.-Powerful musicCons:-Crashing crashing crashing-Lip synch during cut scene is just horrible. They didn't even try.-First half of the bosses were so-so-Lack of keybinding support. There's no way to set up a custom config for a controller.-Lack of enemy variety.-I got lost a lot... Level design is composed of a lot of tight hallways and caverns. No necessarily a con but was bloody annoying after getting lost in the same place 3 times.When it comes down to it it was a great game, albeit short (13.4 hours first run through), fantastic combat that took forever to get the nuances to. Have a guy with a huge shield? You have to have a mace to knock it down. Low armor fast assassin type? Use a short sword or fists. You really have to adapt to who and what you are fighting through out the game or else you'll have to get creative or have a bad time. It took me about 6 hours to get the combat system down right.I picked this up for $20 and it was $20 well spent. The standard $50 is a bit steep for the time spent though there are a lot of incentives to play NG+ more spells, armor, weapons, hidden items, side quests, multiple endings, etc.I pray they make a second one with twice as much content and a wider variety of foes to sink my axe into. All in all I think I've enjoyed this more than Darksouls II and that's saying something. I just wish it was a bit more rounded out."
