76561198010271345,Recommended,265300,13408718,"Posted: 16 December, 2014",all,Beta Ray Bill,"Thought these guys were supposed to be PC game developers. But 60% score on Steam? On Steam?? Check the negative reviews. All complaining of technical issues. It's disheartening, to say the least.Whatever. It's still a good game when it works. The content lacks, but the gameplay doesn't. Feels like Dark Souls but with more thought gone in, instead of difficulty due to large gaps between player and NPC damage/hitpoints. And you shouldn't be suffering more than a couple cheap deaths (if at all) so long as you play it smart.Different tactics can yield widly different results. Surprisingly, rushing the enormous melee boss with my two handed axe jump-slashing at his knees was the best way to win in one instance, where hanging back with a big shield previously was hardly helping at all.The game is short though. And the plethora of technical problems discourage a second run through the story. But hell, if you see it on sale for good, I'd still reccomend it, since the devs at least are releasing patches."
,Recommended,265300,13535058,"Posted: 22 December, 2014",all,Leeson,"Lords of the Fallen did have some crashing issues for me. Fortunately, these were solved after setting my GTX 970 PhysX settings to ""CPU"" instead of ""Auto"" in the Nvidia Control Panel.Although this was disappointing, I simply couldn't stop playing this game! I'll summarise some things I liked/didnt like below.Positives:* The game world is very immersive and so cleverly constructed. You'd be 60% through the game then pop out at a door you found locked like 5-6 hours ago, with a reason to go back there. It really did well to keep you exploring.* The game really rewarded you for opening every chest, smashing every object and generally looking in every nook and cranny for secrets. I wouldn't have gotten half the awesome gear I did if I didn't find every place!* Boss fights are challenging, but not abusively punishing. My gripe with games like Dark Souls which are awesome games is simply the time wasting part. OK, when I die on a boss that's fair enough. I'm happy to take the challenge again, even happy for some EXP penalty. These are all fine by me. What I hated about Dark souls was the fact you had to fight 20+ minutes through the same creeps over and over just to try the boss fight again. Lords of the Fallen alleviates this by keeping the boss fights interesting and challenging, but giving you a checkpoint quite close by. This way, when you die you can go straight back to the boss and try again. No time wasting.* Graphics are pretty awesome, and textures are beautiful.* The game was about 15-16 hours in length, which was fine by me. Ideally, a game should always leave you wanting for that little bit more. And that's what Lords of the Fallen did for me.Negatives:* Story is not very cohesive. It kind of just throws you in and expects you to know all this stuff. There also isn't very memorable characters. The gameplay and exploration is what makes this game a blast, but a great story to go with those mechanics would really perfect it.* Some crashing issues (which seem to be fixed now).* I wish there was a way to keep exploring the world when you've finished the last boss. Instead you have to start New Game + which is essentially the same game all over again with harder enemies and better items. I wish new Game + was more an optional thing and you still had the freedom to go exploring after game is finished. There was some places I hadn't figured out how to get to and I wish I could've done that.All in all, I  highly recommend it. Especially for people who couldn't find much enjoyment in Dark Souls. This game is a bit more forgiving and a great introduction to the genre."
