,Recommended,265300,13842454,"Posted: 4 January, 2015",all,Mister Awesomesauce,"This game shares a lot of obvious mechanical similarities with the souls series but really does stand out as its own title.  This is a relatively linear action rpg with some castlevania esque backtracking and a lot of hidden side quests and rewards for those of us that are itching to explore every nook and cranny ( like souls, but you know where to go nearly all the time to progress the story).  The story is played out through fmv cutscenese and for the most part  the game does a good job of letting you know what's going on and where to go next.  It's not all hand holding however as there are no quest markers or maps.  no, you'll have to get accustomed to the area and recall location names if you intend to follow the leads to that special magical item you're trying to discover.Misc Pros:Leveling and the whole purchasing stats to level thing works similar to dark souls here with its bonfire mechanic.  There are alternate hard mode challenges for each boss that rewards extra loot.  There are challenge portals that appear after a boss is defeated for those that remember to backtrack a little and get some more loot and items.  Mobs are varied enough and the bosses are distinctly unique.Misc Cons:You can't avoid damage in this game so much as mitigate it.  Sure you can avoid a lot of it but theres much you can't or just isn't worth trying.  Second, there are relatively straight forward, clear and linear upgrades for weapons and armor types.  Third; the movesets don't change much from weapon to weapon in each wepon class (ie: all greatswords handle pretty much the same.  Just go with the one with the biggest damage.)That being said this game holds its own as a very good title.  Coming from someone with over 700 hours across the soul titles, i happily played through this game and immediately rolled into a second play through."
