76561198151701608,Not Recommended,265300,31000346,Posted: 7 April,all,LazyBearPaws,"People mention that this game is not Dark Souls and should not be reviewed as if it were a Dark Souls title. That being said, a game creates an experience for the player, and if they made a game influenced by Dark Souls then that relationship will be inherent in the experience because that is how it was designed.The Good: Exploring the level is enticing and bound to create some interesting experiences. The ""bonfire"" mechanic where you can opt out of a character refresh for higher experience points is an interesting take on the checkpoint system for a harcore ARPG.The Okay: The combat is really sluggish and clunky. You need to get used to slower dodge mechanics and a slight input delay if you are coming fresh off of a Souls experience. Once you get used to it, the game is definitely doable and offers a unique challenge. The feeling it provides the player is less of a nimble assassin, or powerful warrior, and more of an old man doing his best not to die. Not bad necessarily, just different.The Bad: Boss Battles and Crashes. The boss battles are very drawn out. This would be fine if there was multiple phases, or that gameplay led to a high paced action battle. As mentioned earlier, the combat is slow. A long slow battle becomes boring. Even when you have been trying over and over again and finally succeed, you don't let out a victory cry, you just feel like you came off a slow day of work and are finally done. This game loves to crash in the second half of boss battles, as if it wasn't tedious enough.This game is a different experience that is not super terrible. They tainted the experience by drawing a lot of influence from Dark Souls and missing the boat on some of the significant elements that created such a strong community. If they modified the bonfire and souls aspects to make it less like dark souls and more like its own game, the experience may have stood out and been judged by its own merit."
