,Not Recommended,265300,12689942,"Posted: 29 October, 2014",all,Chris,"Lords of the Fallen is an action rpg that plays very similarly to Dark Souls though it's a considerably better looking and also a lot more forgiving game.The boss battles i fought before the game got unplayable was very predictable and too passive which makes them too easy to defeat but it doesn't mean you can just slash away and hope to defeat them, the bosses still have attack patterns you must learn to defeat them just like Dark Souls and that in itself makes it feel rewarding just not to the extent of Dark Souls.Lords of the Fallen isn't a straight copy of Dark Souls however and tries to have more focus on the story and have more interactions between Harkyn and npc's to mixed results since the dialogues are often uninteresting and awkward much thanks to the less than stellar lip sync and facial/body expressions which could have used a lot more work to be more natural and the story is nothing to write home about either since it's the usual save the world from demons (Rhogar) that have been done so many times before and better, a generic story is not always a bad thing but it needs to stand out imo  because it have been done so many times and this game fails to do it for me personally.I would argue that yes the story in games like this is less important than the gameplay and therefore i could have overlooked it if the rest of the game was well done but more of that later.As for the main character Harkyn, you are an criminal that tries to atone for his past crimes and while there's potential in that i couldn't connect with him as a character because he feels empty and void of personality it's feels like there's nothing that drives him which obviously his strive for atonement and will to save the world does but the game fails to make that connection with the player.Now to the most important aspects of the game, gameplay and perfomance which i expected a lot from but was left disappointed.I really wanted to like this game and that it would be a worthy rival to Dark Souls and for all it's faults i really liked the gameplay WHEN it WORKS then it feels heavy, satisfying and impactful just like it should but every know and then it gets stuck in it's clunkiness and unresponsiveness and forces you to click several times to strike your enemy and dodge an attack which often makes you miss or fail to dodge in time almost like the animation for it is too slow, also the lock on feels very unprecise and could use more tweakes.Now to to the main offender it's performance which is absolutely horrible, very disappointed and the day one patch didn't do anything for me personally, the game feels very sluggish even when the fps is fine and add constant crashes to that which made me give up when i got to  the commander boss, 7 tries and 7 crashes and 5 of those was near the end of the battle, gg CI gg not acceptable at all and Lords of the Fallen is just another in a long list of broken games that's been rushed out lately and my total playtime yet ended with a staggering amount of 40 crashes.For that reason i can't recommend this game for full price and will wait for a bunch of patches, maybe then it will finally reach some of it's potential and be a fun game, there's a lot of potential in this game but the edges feels way too rough right now.Current Score: 4/10- but if they patches the performance and tweak the gameplay a bit to make it smoother and more responsive then i will happily raise the score to a 7/10 a good but flawed game.Last Words: the score may seem low but be aware this is from my experience with the game and might differ from yours but with these many crashes/bugs it feels unplayable atm and thus i can't justify to spend full price on it until it's sorted out."
