,Not Recommended,265300,23415729,"Posted: 6 June, 2016",all,DEATH,"After completeing the game in only 15 hours, it appears obvious just how much of a rush job this game really was. Poor quality through out the entire game. Lack of enemy variety, clunky combat system and awful sound effects make this game a real bore to play. I pretty much forced myself to playthrough this just to see where it would lead.I have nothing positive to say about this game, it has no redeeming values. Even if you buy this for $5 you aren't going to have a good time. Not even an okay time. This isn't just mediocre, it's poorly executed and riddled with bad design.I can't say I experienced any moment of fun. Everything this game tries to do, other games have done better. You might think ""well it looks pretty good at least"" it really doesn't. To get this game to run at around 45 fps i had to turn off EVERY graphical option and set textures to Medium at 720p. It runs horribly on a brand new gaming PC that runs other current gen games at 60+ fps on 1080p. So needless to say, it looked pretty bad for me.Sound effects are terrible as well. There's about 3 weapon sounds in the game and you will hear them a million times. They don't sound powerful or realistic at all. Many missing sounds for a lot of enemies and environmental things. Cutscenes often feel like they are lacking sounds or the sounds are too quiet or just don't match what you are seeing.I turned the music off because I thought it was pretty awful too. Some of the boss music sounds like a parody of symphonic music and doesn't feel intense at all. The tracks that aren't completely awful are generic at best.It's not a very difficult game either and that's coming from someone who created the worst build possible. I put all my points into HP, MP, stamina and equip load. (I did this because I was under the impression that there would be plenty of faith-scaling weapons since i had one very early in the game) This meant that I couldn't use 90% of the weapons and shields. While I had good defense, probably too much considering I barely took damage in the later half of the game, I couldn't use any weapons or block effectively. I two-handed a weak staff for the first half of the game which took forever to kill anything. Than I finally got a good faith-scaling weapon, grinded super easily and eventually found a super low strength requiring sword that dealt way more damage than the 3 faith weapons i found in the entire game. So i used that for the end game areas.With that, you can get an idea of how poorly balanced the game is. Later weapons in the game completely replace early game weapons as the scaling is completely useless for most weapons. There is no upgrade system either, just a rune slot system for weapons, shields and armor and only the higher strength and agility weapons have slots so none of the weapons i used through out my playthrough had any slots. a completely useless system that i never even got to experience outside of giving my armor extra defense.Bosses are so bad in both design and gameplay. Some are completely broken such as getting stuck in walls or in one case I had a boss completely stand still the whole time as I slowly chipped away at his massive health pool. Most of the bosses have a ton of health so it can take ages to kill them but luckily they are very slow and predictable doing the same moves over and over again. Rolling is mostly useless in this game so you can't roll through most boss attacks so it's a waiting game, you just have to wait for that split second after they perform a combo to get a hit or two in, back away and repeat. This ""technique"" will work on every boss in the game even though it is extremely tedious and with the final boss, there's barely any oppertunities to safely get a hit in. Most of the bosses will ALWAYS knock you down when they hit you, even with heavy armor and really high poise. Ground pounds are very common and will knock you down from a good 15 feet away from the boss.Another example of poor quality is the overabundance of glitches and bugs. It almost seems like nothing really works as fully intended. Hitboxes can be really messed up, getting hit from attacks that don't make physical contact with you or in some luckier cases, boss attacks going right through you but you recieve no damage. If you are casting a spell (which you only get 4 in the whole game) and you get hit towards the end of the long animation, you will recieve the effect of the spell but lose no MP. This made healing during boss fights really easy so I didn't have to rely on potions too much. Slidy collision detection makes walking on stairs really weird. The lock on system is bogus, barely functional. You have about a 10% chance of being able to change target when locked on. Sometimes the camera won't even face the enemy you are locked on to but you still walk toward the enemy, this killed me in quite a few areas involving pitfalls.Level design. It's there and it involves lots of switches, back tracking and locked doors. Early areas aren't so bad, they seem pretty average at first but then you get to the middle of the game and it just gets worse from there. Narrow cooridors, enemy ambushes, floating blocks and jumping across gaps as well as pitfalls galore. Many times I had to look up a guide to find out where to go because progressing through the later game is so convoluted. You need to pull several levers to open one door sometimes, or to move some blocks around to progress. This isn't exactly obvious when you will see a switch next to a gate and expect that switch to do something. You pull the lever, nothing happens. What?!Despite all these problems, I still didn't die too much. Most of the time it felt pretty cheap when I did die. Enemies like the mages can drain your HP really quickly, shoot really fast magic that deals huge damage and knocks you down, cast a buff that drains your stamina and every time you hit them, it deals equal damage to you, these guys can end you very quickly. There are checkpoint crystals in rooms with 3 enemies sometimes so as soon as you die and respawn you are getting attacked. Getting cornered by 2 enemies with greatshields and repeatedly attacks results in no posibilities of survival. Speaking of greatshields, you can't kick through them, attack through them or do ANYTHING to counter them. If you do stagger them, you won't even have enough time to get a SINGLE hit in with how slow these weapons are. Only way I could kill them is with magic which seem to go right through their shields making them easy. Otherwise you would be screwed.The story, ha. It's run of the mill and has poor voice acting and writing. Some of the worst stuff I've seen. Awkward animations that keep repeating when npc's are talking combined with non-existent personalities makes none of the characters appealing or relatable. Even after seeing the ending of this game, I didn't have a clue what I had really done in the game plotwise. I don't even know who the final boss was, just kinda there. I assume it was a certain character but it's never explained why there's a big demon beastie as the final boss. Also plotholes as you can expect. How do the [end game enemies] know I supposedly betrayed them? Nothing here really makes much sense and the world is so generic and boring you won't really care.I think that just about covers everything. The TL;DR version is: don't buy the game. It's garbage. No, really. Don't even think about it. I don't care if it's on sale, it's bad. Really bad, probably much worse than you can imagine. You like Dark Souls? That's cool and all but this is nothing like it. Not even a low budget version of it, it's more like if you had taken Dark Souls and shattered it on the ground and tried to reassemble it but you have several large chunks missing and it just looks hideous. That's Lords of the Fallen."
