,Not Recommended,265300,13627283,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,"Tirigon, the darkest soul","I'd really like to recommend this game, but I cant.I'll explain why below, but first, the good things about this game:The good- The graphics are INCREDIBLE. I'm not even kidding, I dont have a game that looks this good in my Steam library, and it still ran well at maximum settings for me. If good graphics are important to you, you can probably stop reading here and buy LoTF, it looks that good.- interesting world with lots of lore: At first, I didnt quite get into it, but the entire world is really interesting, and I really wish there will be another game in this setting. It's awesome.- the Combat system: It's quite similar to Dark Souls, which is of course a synonym for ""awesome"" in this context, but the animations loook much better. Unlike in Dark Souls, heavy armor is actually useful, so big plus on that. I dare say, if not for the flaws I list below, the combat could be better than DS even.- lots to explore: There's quite a lot of stuff to explore, even though the gameworld isn't that big.Sounds awesome? YEA! This game had huuuge potential to be my personal game of the year. Sadly, it was a big disappointment though:The Bad- balance is really, really f*cked up: The very same kind of enemy that is almost boringly easy might oneshot you in the next area. And there is no indication you're in a challenge area or anything, it seems just random.- boss and some enemy design is abysmal: Where Dark Souls nailed the principle of ""hard, but fair"" perfectly, LoTF instead creates difficulty by unfairness. There is lots of attacks that are seemingly undodgeable, some bosses are almost a DPS race, enemy recovery frames are incredibly fast while your own are slow as hell.... For one type of shielded enemy I actually found the most efficient strategy to wear the heaviest armor and just bash away hoping they'll die quicker than I - this isn't how a fighting game should be like!- slow-mo combat: The PC is incredibly slow - quickrolling is similar to Dark Soul's Fatrolling! This wouldn't be too bad if the enemy were similarly slow, but they arent - see the ""unfair"" comment above.- great lack of enemy variety: There's only like 4 or 5 enemies that are REALLY different from each other, mostly it's the same thing with more HP and a different look throughout the game. This is disappointing, because what little enemies there are are really well designed.- too short: I beat the game in 17 hours. For Scale: The first Dark Souls took me 50 on the first playthrough....- lack of map: I mentioned exploration and how beautiful the game is above, but some maps are so confusing that travellig through them without a map or anything is a chore rather than fun.Summary and TL;DRThis game had so much potential - it could easily have been one of the best games ever, and for that reason I really hope there will be a sequel someday.Sadly, though, it fails in the details and in the end, I found the game frustrating and unfair rather than challenging and fun.You might still want to pick it up on a sale, but I really cant fully recommend this game. Sadly."
