76561197987791260,Not Recommended,265300,12686964,"Posted: 29 October, 2014",all,CH@S3R,"UPDATED (see below)The good:1. Graphics: in short, it looks awesome! Really a good looking game with spectacular video effects.2. Sound: nice and immersive sound that really makes me proud of having a sound card.3. Level design: the game world is so intricate that you will literally get lost from time to time.The bad:1. Optimization/bugs: 40 minutes into the game => crashTwo hours into the game => very bad FPS, restart or crashAfter reaching the next major location in the game I got 3 crashes in one hour.Some video settings occasionaly get reset to default (vertical sync and post processing are most common).Post processing enables a filter that makes the game look like you need 3D glasses (red and blue) when looking at the edges of objects that are not in the center of the screen. Very weird...2. Control: no matter if you use a mouse + keyboard or a controller, you are bound to look like a chump from time to time due to the awkward control scheme with either funny results or great frustration for missing a spell or a dodge.Trying to dodge forward while sprinting makes the character jump and then roll. This is the most useless and anti-enjoyment thing ever, IMHO. Who in this world makes a control scheme that has two simultaneous actions at one button press ?3. Gameplay: the collisions are dubious at best, sometimes ""catching"" a corner when running or dodging, stopping you dead in your tracks.Also, the invisible collisions prevent the lock on enemies unless a clear path is between you and them (can't lock on an enemy through jail bars, for example).Selective gravity... this is a bummer. I push an enemy from a ledge, nothing happens to him but if I fall the same way I lose hp. Really, developers ?!Enemy balancing issues... another big bummer. The ""small"" enemies are tougher than the area bosses. You can whistle your way through a boss fight only to die when a leprechaun kicks your butt with a toothpick.Overall a Dark Souls clone that tries to make the progress difficult in a dubious manner, at the expense of good gameplay.10/10 for sound and graphics7/10 for gameplayUPDATE:OK, my initial review was a little too harsh so after two more hours into the game I'm starting to get the hang of it.Initially I reviewed it from a Dark Souls player's perspective, having played DS1 and DS2 + all DLC's multiple times and... well... it's different, I'll give you that!Unlike the above mentioned games, Lotf seems to want to have the player to use all the things at his disposal in order to advance and have success.Without any spoilers, I have to say that choosing any class and trying to play it in a preset manner (say that you want to go full big axe melee) is pretty much a no-no. You have to become versatile in order to do well.How you manage that it's entirely up to you. Just bear in mind that you need to play the game how the developers imagined it and now how you want.The gameplay score was changed from the 5 to a 7 and I can say that it starts to look better the more I play it.Oh, one more thing. Make sure you have more than 8gb of RAM in your PC.It says that 8gb is recommended, but you need to give the game almost 8gb and not have Windows chew 1gb and the background programs another 1.Note: Do not change the controls and then press Escape once and then click on Resume. You will end up on a blackscreen. Tested and it's 3 out of 3 so far... consider yourselves warned.All right... completed the game.Another big drawback is the cheap difficulty added to the final boss.I ploughed through the game using magic, even got the 'zero damage in a boss fight' achievement in the second last boss, only to find that the last one is immune to magic...So the last battle was fought in melee only, with my character molded to magic. Lucky for the exploration and getting some useful stuff and thanks to the lack of merchant so that I couldn't sell it...Anyway, I keep my review and do not recommend this game.Sure, it's fun at times and the graphics and sound are fantastic, but that's about it. I can't ignore the fact that it looks like the developers cut some corners in the design.Also, true to its behavior, at the end I watched a nice cinematic, the credits and pressed the Quit button.Well... crash!"
