,Not Recommended,265300,13170920,"Posted: 30 November, 2014",all,Mymothersmeatloaf,"There was no option for a yes and no answer so I'll just put a no to save the people considering this game the trouble.I'm not hating on it because it is a souls clone, considering the fact that within the couple hours playing I have enjoyed it a bit, these are just problems that stand out.In it's current state, it is very playable, yes, but the amount of issues with the game itself make it hard to even begin where to start, I have not had any crashing, yes I've had rediculous amounts of framerate issues and optimization issues but that is the least of the troubles.To begin with, I have played dark souls 1 & 2 and yes I have beaten them both, numerous times at that, at least a couple hundred hours worth, the bosses in those games were fun, interesting, and very difficult at that, but every encounter you had with a boss made you begin to learn it's tactics, strategies and attack patterns whilst also taking the amount of damage you make into account with your stats while fighting the boss. Lords of the fallen feels like it has a set damage for all the bosses, which makes almost all the bosses entirely annoying, repetitive and pretty boring to have to fight over and over again unlike souls bosses which sometimes make you want to fight them again. The attacks the bosses make also feel very forced and similar to each other with only a few new attacks obviously setting them apart from eachother. Most bosses will sometimes summon enemies to help them fight you, which can get really annoying really fast considering 90% of the enemies I have encountered do nothing but spam their shield over and over, which brings me to another issue, blocking enemies.You're going to see me comparing tihs game with souls games a lot. Mostly because the games are blatantly similar. In souls games it was possible to shield bash and even break an enemies gaurd by kicking them or by pushing them in dark souls 2. This made fighting enemies with shields very doable and balanced out the annoying hollows with spears enemies that you would encounter mostly during the beggining of both the games. LOTF has gaurd break options, but the stun lasts so shortly that it makes it damn near impossible for you to even get a single hit in to the enemies. the enemies with shields are so game breaking that the only options you have are to parry/backstab fish the hell out of them, or run into them constantly and hope you don't get hit while dishing out a few good solid hits.Story -While I'm somebody who doesn't really care much for story in games I will say the game's is pretty mediocre/cliche at best.Optimization issues -While I haven't had any real problems with the game crashing or anything like that, I had been experiencing a lot of fps lag which makes fighting extremely difficult, now, my system meets the system requirements more than it should, I'm able to play it on high as my settings defaulted to that, but it uses a lot of experimental technology which makes it hard to run on systems which are more than enough to play the game.If you can get past ALL of these problems I think you will see the good in the game, but for me, until these issues are resolved I think I'll be sticking with the souls series for now."
