,Not Recommended,265300,13672801,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,bladechild,"It seems to be taboo for any Souls fan to slate this game. Apparently you have to adapt to the different style of play and accept it.The problem is this game was an obvious attempt at capitalizing on the Souls' games success, yet at the same time, the game doesn't really know what it wants to be.The combat is a threeway mess of Souls type meleeing, Generic action RPG button bashing with overpowered and clumsy spells, and terrible RPG stat mechanics.Gameplay is intentionally clunky and slow, which isn't a problem in of itself. It's just poorly executed. if you want to create a realistic, reactionary melee style, everything has to be fair and on an even playing field (ala Monster Hunter). Instead all enemies possess far greater poise, stamina and speed, making general combat a case of hope swinging and damage sponging with heavy armor. All enemies seem capable of shield-upping after swinging far too quickly. Same applies from recovering from poise breaks. The enemy just outruns even the swiftest of sword playstyles in your arsenal. So you are just left to cheesing the game with the overpowered spells and a rather amusing tactic of using the run-strong attack, which few enemies seem to wise up to. As for why the run-strong attack strikes 3x the speed of a normal standing attack, I don't know. It's one of the many technical flaws in this game.Also, enemies can change attack aim in mid execution. That's a rule 101 breaker right there.In summary, slow, clunky, tedious."
