,Not Recommended,265300,12702114,"Posted: 30 October, 2014",all,Broseff,"You may notice I have very few hours on this. Most people would consider that a bad point and would not pay attention to my thoughts on the game, because how could I possibly have formed an opinion when I obviously haven't finished the game? The reason I have this few hours is because it only took this long for me to not even want to continue.This game wants to be Dark Souls. Now, I love Dark Souls, but I'm no fanboy. In fact, I'm extremely new to the Dark Souls type game, but I do like it and I do like the gameplay. It's tough as hell, but fair and relies on you to master your weapons, character and environment. This game is tough in a different way, but not a good way. All your standard enemies are very easy to take care of and don't provide much challenge. In fact, any part of this game that is outside of the Lord (boss) areas is pretty linear and just... Boring. Not much effort required to clear the path and find your next objective. The next objective is usually ""Kill this Lord and come talk to me"".The first Lord was interesting, his health bar is separated into quarters, and each quarter changed the way he fought. I had to adapt on the fly. Overall, it was a great experience and was a very satisfying fight. The following Lords were not so, they didn't change when their health reached a segment, and their difficulty relied on spawning in helper enemies to harass you while you try to fight the Lord. That's not difficulty by design, that's cheap difficulty.The problem with this is, the controls do not respond well enough for me to fight more than one enemy at a time. Each hit makes me stumble, regardless of it being blocked (which by the way, 100% blocking shield doesn't mean 100% blocking in this game for some reason) and several enemies have enough speed to land a bunch of hits on you in amount of time it takes you to recover and control yourself at all. It doesn't take long for it to become a small cycle that puts you all the way from full health down to death and you haven't been able to regain control yet. The controls are sluggish and kind of unresponsive which isn't entirely good for a game that wants you to soldier through bosses that give you very little window to actually do damage.The Lord that made me quit relied on these spawning tactics to keep beating me down for an entire 1hr+ long session. Each attempt lasted around 5 minutes, so you can understand why I would become frustrated. When his health reached a segment, he responded with an AoE attack that covered the entire area. Oh, and it's a one hit kill. And I have little buggers attacking me and forcing me out into dangerous areas. If the little buggers don't kill me, that AoE does. Repeat process. Again. And again. And again.The game is very pretty, but this aspect also suffers. My machine has a fair amount of power behind it, and has managed to run modern games like a dream. The most modern probably being Shadow of Mordor. I ran that on max settings and it had no trouble at all. This game, however, stutters like crazy. I managed to fix this by turning off the awful Post-Processing effects. Not only did this greatly improve performance, it looks a lot nicer, too. It looks like a dark, wartorn environment instead of a JJ Abrams movie.The voice acting is subpar at best. I don't know who voiced Harkyn, but I'm not sure he's aware he's meant to appear to be talking to other people. It sounds a bit like someone talking into a mirror in the deepest voice they can muster. Honestly, he sounds like a creepy pervert talking down the phone to his current stalking victim. Maybe that's what he was in prison for, who knows? I for sure don't as I didn't finish the story. Also, when your energy bar depletes he starts breathing very heavily like he's jerking off. Maybe he was a pervert.If you want Dark Souls, don't expect much because it doesn't really play anywhere near the same. I really wish this could've been better. It looked so promising, but didn't quite cut it for me. Disappointing."
