76561198063895034,Recommended,265300,18580282,"Posted: 20 October, 2015",all,lordjosh9000,"I have seen a few reviews saying this game has a confusing story/poor story element, yet all I ever hear is praise for Dark Souls when it's story is basically ""you're dead, kill these people and it might help"". While despite playing Dark Souls several times it couldn’t hold my attention, and I have beaten Lords of The Fallen. But I digress...on to the review.I like Lords of The Fallen in most areas. I think the combat is reminiscent of Fable on the original Xbox which in my opinion was responsive and fun. Locking on has some quarks but is easy to get used too. Spells and the gauntlet add some diversity to the combat but do not break the game, like in Dark Souls where magic is easy mode. (It may seem like I am bashing DS but I’m not. I like DS but it is the only game I have to compare this one to as it is obviously inspired by DS.) Bosses do lack visual diversity in a since but their skills are varied enough to make each one feel like a new experience.I absolutely love the art style in this game. It is rare for the lead character in a game to not only act like a badass, but to look like one as well. Harkyn is certainly both of those things. He looks inspired by Ragnar Lothbrok from Vikings and is just as hardened. It is refreshing to get away from the stereo typical ""why did this happen to me"" lead, and see one man up to the task without whining about it. The game is grainy and dark in tone for a mature feeling.  Gothic and Viking inspired architecture is pleasing to the eye and feels ominous. Armor and weapons seem to have been inspired by the dark ages mixed with the absurd scale used in Warhammer 40k; making you feel indestructible and enemies look menacing.The difficulty in the game at first is frustrating. Never on the same level as DS but early on you will die frequently to even standard enemies. But by endgame Harkyn can tank blows from even the final boss and carries more than enough potions. Some people do not like the feeling of godliness in a game, but I enjoy it as it satisfying when character progression feels like it has payed off. Leveling up and gaining new gear can make you unbeatable, and I feel like every game should allow the player to become a god of death if that is how they want to play.Overall I think Lords of The Fallen is a solid game. It lacks some polish but the important mechanics feel good, and most major bugs have been patched by this point. I did not experience even one crash during my play through, and the hit detection was spot on. Every time I died it was my fault. At around 20 hours to beat with all side quests and secrets I do not think the game is worth $50, but if you can find it on sale at half that or less pick it up."
76561197999400310,Recommended,265300,19054476,"Posted: 13 November, 2015",all,pinkslip,Died on the way to surpass Dark Souls.7/10 for gerne fans
