76561198020971127,Not Recommended,265300,16801689,"Posted: 29 June, 2015",all,Sventorious,"I went into this game with really high hopes, but it left me wanting a lot more.I hate to say it, but it's basically the arcade version of the souls games. I'm sure a lot of people really enjoy it, but it's just not for me :(pros-*Beautiful graphics..That's about it.cons-*Extremely clunky and weighted controls.*Boring story (opinion)*Inferior clone of ""souls"" combat*Two handed weapons are comically slow*Poor class diversity*No real sense of character customization*nothing feels unique"
76561197999209957,Not Recommended,265300,16754399,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,Cyanni,"This game is incredibly pretty to look at, and the way your weapons and armor impact your movement and fighting style is something I wish more games would implement. The attack animations of heavy weapons like the Cleric's hammer definitely feel well done -- you can practically feel the impact of them in your chair. From a purely visual feast standpoint this game is at least an 8 out of 10.All of the good, unfortunately, pales in comparison to the bad. And there is a lot of bad going on in this game. Thankfully, the first boss does a terrific job of calling attention to most of the problems.The collision/hit detection is terrible. When combined with the frustrating way that enemy attacks track you despite dodging/rolling (making them largely pointless as defensive abilities go), you will be taking a lot of damage even when you were sure you had successfully evaded an attack. An enemy in the midst of the downward stroke of a massive overhead two-handed axe attack will rotate with you while you roll, so an attack that you think will impact the floor at 12 o'clock will follow you as you roll all the way to 3 o'clock. You'll take damage, and likely curse a bit.Add in the incredibly clunky, unresponsive controls and fighting becomes even more of a challenge because you're fighting both the monsters and the controls. The attack animations for your character are very well done, and you get ample opportunity to appreciate them because when you start one you are committed to it until it finishes or the monster(s) knock you backwards on your butt. There is no breaking off an attack for a quick roll, parry, or block. You'll take more damage than you do, and probably curse a bit. This leads to a lot of stick and move fighting which is a terrifc way of making fights more realistic than standing toe-to-toe hacking away at each other, but that kind of fighting relies heavily on spot-on, responsive controls, which Lords of the Fallen falls woefully short on delivering.Now, a positive of this game is that it does provide a challenging ""Souls""-like game, which is a nice refreshing change of pace in a world of games that seems to practically want to hold your hand from the starting line to the finishing line. However, when I think of challenging games, I think of things that make me use my head, employ strategy, evolve what I'm doing to overcome a new obstacle. I don't consider bad controls and cheap AI trickeration as a legitimate part of making a challenging game. Imagine climbing Mt. Everest with an anvil chained around your waist while abominable snowmen fire rockets at you that never miss.You'd die, and probably curse a little bit. But you might enjoy that more than playing Lords of the Fallen."
76561198015502624,Recommended,265300,20401734,"Posted: 8 January, 2016",all,Darthelmet,"I think the best way to describe this game is it's your first ""dark souls"" game, although I don't mean that in a bad way. I bought this along with both dark souls games and after getting frustrated with DS1 I gave it a pause and tried out this one.In a lot of important ways, the game is way easier to jump into as a first timer to the genre than dark souls was. The game runs smoothly right out of the box. I didn't need to go and install mods and dig through .ini files just to get it working. I don't recall ever experiencing a major bug or crash in game, it looks amazing, and most importantly the controls felt pretty tight and intuitive. It's difficult for me to describe why, but something about the way the character moves and dodges attacks felt easier to me in this game, which makes boss fights with massive bosses who swing at you way more tolerable. The game also feels quite a bit smaller and directed than dark souls. While you do have the freedom at certain points in the game to go off and explore areas you shouldn't be exploring yet, you usually can't get too far off track and the game's story will usually guide you in a general direction you need to go in. On top of this, the entire game basically takes place within a single monestary and one side area. While I felt like this limited the scope of the story from being epic, it did have the effect of making the game feel more completeable.There were a few things about the game that I was kind of iffy on though. First off, in addition to my main playthrough as a warrior character, I also tried playing through part of the game as a rogue. It felt extremely underpowered to the point where it felt like trying to play the game with a handicap. While it can be fun to sneak up on smaller enemies and backstab them for a quick kill, against larger enemies, particularly ones with a good shield, it felt nearly impossible to beat them. On the warrior character you can just stand up to them, block a few attacks, then use your weapon's impact to break their stance and kill them. With the rogue, you need to get behind them for a backstab, but the enemies which should have been slow, lumbering tanks were able to turn around with great speed to block me and sometimes randomly smack me with a one shot attack. I ended up with a lot of deaths where I felt that I couldn't have done anything about it.Another issue I have with the game is the way bosses are balanced and the way their special weapon achievements work. Generally speaking, against most bosses, even if you are in pretty heavy plate armor with a really good tower shield, their attacks are usually so powerful that it isn't worth trying to tank them. Not only do they do a lot of damage even through a block, but they will usually knock you down and/or apply some other harmful effect. This means that despite whatever build you wanted to play on your character, the best strategy for most bosses is to strip down to light armor or even go nude and just dodge everything. On top of this, all bosses have a special way of killing them which makes them drop an upgraded version of their item. While this seems like a cool concept in theory, in practice, a lot of the achievements make you play the game in a playstyle that doesn't always make sense for whatever the item is. For example (minor gameplay related spoilers)the first boss's special weapon is a powerful greatsword that deals a special heavy attack when used in one hand with a shield. The way you get this weapon is to kill the boss without taking any damage from him. The second boss's special drop is a massive tower shield with a special block ability and the way you get this drop is to beat the boss without blocking any attacks. So in both cases, the way you get items which are basically only relevant to a heavy armor tank is to get naked and dodge everything. It feels really wierd that I can't use my character's build on most of the bosses in the game effectively.Another issue I had with the game, which I could argue as maybe being a positive for new players, is that the game actually gets easier as you get later in the game. Part of this is just getting used to the controls, but I think part of the issue is that the gear you get is absurdly powerful. By the end of the game, I could barely take any damage on trash and I killed most of them in 1-2 hits. The bosses still hurt enough that I had to go with light armor dodging, but most of them had so little health compared to my damage output that the fights just didn't last long enough to be serious challenges. If I could avoid their initial attacks, my first chance to attack them would often take off between 25-40% of their life. I killed the final boss on my first try pretty quickly even though I was letting him heal for an achievement. Maybe NG+ would have been more of a challenge, but I don't really have an interest in replaying the game with bigger numbers.Finally, I wasn't thrilled with the way the story and choices worked out in the game. Major story spoilers ahead:The game has a few points when you are forced to make a choice which in theory should influence the way the game plays out later. However, a lot of them are really unclear about what the choices actually entail and in the end don't seem to matter that much. The biggest example of this is at the very end of the game. The last lord drops a powerful rune that gives your gear a big but boring buff. When you go talk to the runesmith, he acknowleges you have the rune, won't tell you anything useful about it, and then gives you the choice to use it on a weapon, on armor, or to give it to him. I'm given no context for why this choice matters or why I'd ever give up my upgrade to him. Plus, unless you actually give it to him, the other choices don't actually lock you into doing anything. You can tell him you want it on your weapon then put it on armor instead, or forget to wear it altogether because it was in a different piece of armor like I did, and that somehow counts as giving it to him. Turns out, all this decision does other than buff your items, is decide who you favor at the end of the story, either the humans, the demons, or the balance. I'm given no reason why my choice with the rune leads to this outcome and it's such a throwaway point in the story that I'm not even sure why they bring it up. It's sort of just dumped in the final cutscene as an afterthought along with the rest of the quick wrapup of what your choices did.So overall, I think this is a decent game. It has its flaws, but I think as someone's first step into this genre of games its a pretty good one to get started with. It will be a reasonably quick but enjoyable experience that should let you see if you like these kinds of games."
