,Recommended,265300,12705343,"Posted: 31 October, 2014",all,KZRSoze,"Update: Ok so I just beat the final boss. Overall I liked this game a lot. It remained challenging and fun throughout. There are tons of extra things to do, secrets to find and places to go revisit, much like a Metroid game. As I played I never really felt super powerful, like I could just breeze through enemies. It also never got super frustrating the way Dark Souls did for more.The biggest differences in this regard for me are:1. There aren't many poison enemies and poison doesn't last too long.2. There are no curses.3. When fighting in a tight space you don't have to worry about you weapon hitting a wall.4. There aren't many places you need to do precise jumps and there aren't large sections with narrow areas where you have to worry about falling constantly.Personally this game is what I hoped Dark Souls 1 would be. I haven't tried Dark Souls 2 yet, maybe its more like this. I was very pleased with Lords of the Fallen and will be eagerly awaiting some DLC or a sequel.(Additional Note): New Game + seems pretty cool so far. You start the game over from the beginning with all of your gear and a new skill tree of one of the other classes in addition to the skills you already have. All of the enemies are tougher and are a match for your gear.Old Review after a couple hours of gameplay-----------------------------------------------------------------------I'll be completely honest up front. I'm not the biggest fan of the Demon/Dark Souls games. This game DOES play much like those games, but in a much less frustrating way.So far I have explored the first couple areas and beaten the first 2 bosses. I find it quite challenging while not making me want to break my controller in half. I feel like it’s a nice middle ground and that people who like Dark Souls could probably get some enjoyment out of it as well.The artwork is beautiful and the production values are high.The only thing that looks a bit janky is the conversation animations. The lip syncing is pretty bad.It seems like they spent most of their time making the enemy animations look great and never got around to polishing the conversations. It’s pretty minor, but still noticeable.Bugs I have encountered:-With NVIDIA Turbulence turned on it looks like fireworks going off across the screen in outdoor areas. Makes it hard to see, but the game still looks great with this option disabled.-Weird issue with the left thumb stick on my XB1 controller not responding correctly when moving or trying to select menus down to the right. 360 controller works fine, so I'll be using that instead.- Framerate seems to stay around 30-35 fps with vsync on or off. Maybe my video card just isn't powerful enough for it to get any higher. Still very playable, IMO.Overall I really like this game and I think after another patch or two it will be running perfectly, at least for me. I recommend it to those seeking a challenging game. It plays like a more refined Dark Souls with a more realistic Darksiders kind of fantasy art style. Prepare to Die.....Some More??"
