76561198030549296,Recommended,265300,14297632,"Posted: 2 February, 2015",all,iloshwdgac,"Graphics: 1.5/3Story: .5/3Game Play: 2/3Re-playable: .5/1Sale Rate: 40%Total: 4.5/10Graphics: 1.5/3This is a mixed point. The textures are amazing, but are not optimized. My computer with 8 GB of ram, 1 GB of video ram, I5 2320 with 3.3 GHz processor the game lags on all setting until I turn off V-sync. If you have a current gen gaming computer, the game will look good, but with normal computers or 3 years dated one like me, you will have Lords of the Fallen FPS. The lip syncing on the setting I was on was laughably bad. Multiple objects faded in and out of existence both in cut scenes and normal play. The best was a woman shaking over ledge yelling to herself about stealing her dagger only to spawn a scared monk when I told her the dead tell no tales.Story: .5/3You play as a grizzled old man that has just been set free from jail. It is now his job to save the world from an ancient fallen god. To stop you, the god sends multiple Lords. Along your way you find enough sane people to count on 2 HANDS.The game has a similar style to Dark Souls where you are thrown into a world with a cut scene. Unlike Dark Souls, you have NPC’s to guide you. They are just far enough away from each other that you forget about them and get annoyed every time you see them. The dialog is dry and invoke little response from the player. Too much dialog to create your own story and not enough to depict the world.Game Play: 2/3Very similar to Dark Souls with 2 main differences. The first is how it treats its “bonfires”. Lords of the Fallen has a gamble system, where the more enemies you kill, the more exp. you get for killing them. You get about 2% more for each consecutive kill until you either rest or level up. When you die, you lose you exp. slowly until you pick it up. If you wait and fight around where you died, you get a slow health regen. When you do finally level up you can spend the exp. into two banks, attribute point and spell point. You can level these partially so every time you level you leave with no exp.The second difference is in the equipment. In Dark Souls, you can use your starting gear until the end of the game. Finding ways to upgrade it to make it end game worthy. In Lords of the Fallen, every level has a full set of three type of armor, lite, medium, and heavy. By the end of the game, the first heavy armor has lower stats than late game lite armor. You might be able to use equipment for more than one level, but unlikely. As such, the game as a frantic search for the next best item to beat the level. It has no natural growth, forcing you to rely on the finding a new item compared to learning a weapon over a game and seeing the weapon grow with the character over the game.The actual combat is slower Dark Souls without range damage and spell being more support than damage dealing. The starting class has three different starting equipment and three different magic’s. Your choice adjust your starting stats, but after the second boss you can respects your character, so the only important choice is the magic. The magic has three distinct versions, but they all work equally well with any play style.Re-Playability: .5/1The game has a new game plus letting you continue with your stats and equipment, otherwise no new content. you might want to start a new game to play through with a different starting class, but the weapons are not classed based, and there are several weapons that should not be in the other classes, like an axe that requires dex, or a pole ax that needs int.Should you buy it?The game feels like a first attempt by a new company to make a Dark Souls. It feels unpolished and glitchy, but there is a lot of heart in it. It has some good ideas but is unbalanced and un-optimized. Buy it on a sale and it would be a good buy."
76561198080123531,Recommended,265300,13753134,"Posted: 31 December, 2014",all,Epik Kai,"Pretty good game. It plays almost exactly like Dark Souls but it's A LOT EASIER. I enjoyed the game during the time I played it because there were multiple weapons to choose from that you could get from rare drops from enemies or the bonus drops from killing bosses. Every piece of equipment was unique aesthetically but didn't always bring any special effect to make it ""unique."" The game was ridiculously short and only had about 7 bosses I believe, I didn't care much for the story either since it was pretty underwhelming considering the ending was kind of just rushed, the final fight didn't even have dialogue LOL. It only took me about 8 hours to complete the main story with a little exploring here and there. Besides following the main plot and farming monsters for experience, there were optional ""Challenge Portals"" that you could enter into to win some sweet gear. The challenges differ and are probably my favorite part of the game because it was a nice change of pace from the main story. However, there were incentives for replaying the game in ""New Game+."" They offered slightly tougher enemies and a couple of new weapons you can find. ""New Game++"" didn't really have much, I believe it offered only one or two more weapons that you could get but besides that, ""New Game++"" is basically just ""New Game+"" but just a bit more difficulty added into the mix. All in all, the game was enjoyable for the time that I spent playing it, was it worth the $50 I got it for? No. I say wait for another sale on steam and get it. Probably for $20-$30. In the end I give it......mmmmmmm........1/10 MUST PLAY GAME OF THE YEAR HEIL GABEN."
