,Not Recommended,265300,13671029,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,Faroh,"There's a reason this game has such mixed reviews. In fact, I've never felt more ambivalent about a game before. I'll try to break this down into the good and bad, with an expanded version down below.For those who don't want to read a long review, I'll say this:If it isn't on sale, it isn't worth buying.I'll expand on this later.Good:- Great looking game - armor/weapons/scenery/weapons- Fun different styles of play/different class combos- Fun spells (caveat here, sometimes there is no way to use your spells which is annoying and makes a spellcaster class of any sort somewhat impossible, more on this later.)- Overall fun/challenging game.Bad:- Still somewhat buggy/optimization issues for PC - IE binding to a certain key caused my game to freeze up and crash, had issues playing in Fullscreen mode (couldn't click on things, was gamebreaking issue).- Very poor pacing/storyline. In fact, the ""choices"" you are given which affect the story mean absolutely nothing to you because the story is so poorly developed. But, not to worry, all you get is a ♥♥♥♥♥♥ narrated cutscene at the end that has no real weight to it anyways.- Irritating camera angles when fighting in close quarters (which is a lot). Also, a lot of times you're put in a narrow hallway with a heavily armored enemy with a giant shield and strafing around them is impossible.- My biggest issue with the game was the poor direction.I ended up skipping an ENTIRE AREA/BOSS FIGHTon accident because I took a ""secret"" path which caused me to miss talking to a guy who sent you into another dimension and progressed the storyline. I spent about 2-3 hours trying to beat an area that was scaled way too high and even made it to the boss before I found a guide online and realized what had happened. BAD game design in my opinion.EXPANDED VERSION:Overall, I enjoyed the game, but damn it has it's problems. I read the reviews here and didn't think much of the gripes. But they're justified and frustrating, and at one point I'd wished I hadn't bought the game at all.Due to the bugs with the keybinds/fullscreen mode, I ended up having to replay several areas over entirely.Due to the horrible story design, I missed an entire area and had to play the entire thing over after I had figured out I wasn't even supposed to be there yet. (Although it was MUCH easier the second time around.) But trust me when I say the story the entire game feels unfinished and just plain bad. For a game that looks as good LotF, the story really seems like it was written hurriedly by a 5th grader or something. Half the time hearing the dialogue I found myself saying ""what..? why?...alright...I guess."" It was just very poorly developed, and the dialogue choices sometimes didn't even match, I recall someone saying ""The [thing] isn't a threat"" and my character said ""All the more reason to destroy it""....like, what?Some of the scaling seems off. I went from being able to demolish any enemy in way to getting stomped by mobs toward the end - I suppose it's possible I didn't do enough of the side-questing, however, the side-quests are very unclear and cumbersome. From what I could find, I didn't see anywhere to read about where I was supposed to actually go to complete a lot of my sidequests. I did some of them, but never found an opportunity to turn them in. I attribute this problem to the poor story direction/design that I already mentioned.The game did have it's fun points though. I enjoyed the combat - I went light armor and dual wield weapons/staff, so I did a lot of rolling around and dodging more than blocking. A big complaint I have, though, was upon meeting the larger, armored ""elite"" enemies, their huge swinging near-one-shotting attacks didn't leave much of a window for counter-attacks, which I thought was stupid. You're more or less required/forced to use your spells/gauntlet to take down some enemies, which I also didn't care for. Why would I weave and dodge around an enemy when it's easier just to spam the gauntlet and chunk his HP down? Only limit to doing it is your Magic bar.Now seems like a good time to point out, this game tried really hard to be like Dark/Demon's Souls, however, then it tries NOT to be. Like mentioned above, it basically forces you to use your spells/gauntlet to be effective, even if you're not really specialized in them. So, I found myself dumping points into Faith because I had to, not really because I wanted to. But I will say, the game got *stupidly* easier once I used some of my Cleric spells - one had a damage shield/reflect that also healed, the other stunned any enemy that attacked me and damaged them. Much much easier.Casting these spells however, is nothing but a chore. They have long cast times, and if you don't cast them before entering a fight, good luck. You're going to HAVE to dodge around a corner and hope you can get the spell off, and the AI seems programmed to attack you when you start casting. If my spells weren't centered around shielding/healing a lot of the times I'm pretty certain I would have died just trying to cast them - I definitely got hit *A LOT* before the animation finished, but the spell still went off.However, once I got around the idea of trying to play Dark Souls style and embraced that stupid gauntlet and my death-trap-cast spells, the game became a lot easier and a lot more enjoyable (when I wasn't skipping entire chunks of it inadvertently). Most the time is spent fighting so I tended to just kind of ignore the story - maybe next go around I'll pay more attention to the side-quests and ""storylines"".Ultimately, my advice is this:- Only buy this game if it's on sale. Seriously, it's not worth more than 20 bucks.- USE A GUIDE. Just do it. The game is far too ambiguous and counter-intuitive. If you're lost or stuck or having trouble, I'd recommend looking up a guide and just sticking with it. The game just doesn't do a good job of explaining much anything.- Try to use every tool at your disposal at all times. A guide here on combat mechanics might help, I spent a lot of time kind of figuring it out.- Remember the game is crappy and if you find yourself playing in a way that seems cheap or ridiculous that you're on the right track.This is a fun game that you can enjoy playing for a little while. However, the entire game takes about 10 hours to beat. Given the very short and shallow story, the bugs, and the overall lack of polish, I can't recommend this game ESPECIALLY as listed at full price for 50 dollars. I would have had SEVERE buyer's remorse.If you can snag it for 20 like I did, or 25, I'd say it might be worth it, especially if you really enjoy this genre."
