,Recommended,265300,12679405,"Posted: 29 October, 2014",all,Starman,"This is a hard game to recommend, but I am going to do so anyways. Something is off about the game, and it's really hard to say why. In terms of combat, it's a  very visceral, if not effective and very satisfying heavy version of the combat you would find in a souls game. The control layout is almost 100% identical except for how rolls are handled and a few other things. Being able to charge your attacks is a nice touch. You will love the combat......and then you will hate it as soon as you love it. The problem is kind of straight forward. It's the enemies. It's not that the enemies are hard, and it's not because their tells aren't dramatic, it's the fact that they drag out an already slow combat to a very frustrating snails pace. It's all fun and games until you encounter a kite shield enemy. If you encounter two at the same time, might as well set up camp, you'll be there a while. The problem with the kite enemies is that you are meant to punish them by shield breaking their guard or waiting for them to attack so they open themselves up, however guard break is all but ineffective against these types of enemies. The only way I have been able to break through their guard is with heavy two handed attacks with a polesword weapon. This is fine and all, but it takes away everything once you realize this and can just mash 2handed attacks.Everything kind of just bleeds together in this game. From a visuals and a gameplay perspective. It's really tough to clarify. It kind of just feels like a fever dream. It's a very disorienting game with the lower frames, heavy graphics, and the weird movement speed.  There is a story that is primarily told through audio logs, but even that doesn't seem all that interesting.I don't see the point just yet in choice between 3 classes. You can obtain the armor types and the weapon types of all the classes on one character. I want to start another file to check that out. I haven't really touched the spells at all so no comment there.The graphics look nice. the main character reminds me of if you took a space marine from warhammer into an elder scrolls type of game and decked him out.The enemy types are fairly boring. The gear is kind of eh.The checkpoint system in this game is fairly similar to the bonfire system in dark souls with one major difference: when you rest at a checkpoint, the enemies will not respawn. It seems enemies only respawn when you die. But what this means is you can pretty much farm really easily with zero penalty in doing so. Yeah, your experience multiplier suffers but it's not a massive deal. I feel that the ability to bank your xp in either spells or attribute skill points is cool, but I wish they would have incorporated a way to put in an exact number. Right now it's highly sensitive to that trigger press and you tend to overshoot how much you wanted to bank.Overall, I am going to recommend it, but with a warning. I don't feel the game is worth full price, and it's a very disorienting game."
