76561198018682798,Recommended,265300,22144271,"Posted: 30 March, 2016",all,kso87,"Let me start by saying that this review is my opinion and in no way law with regards this game.This game has been sitting in my playlist for over a year and I’ve been dying to like it. I have taken a few tentative steps on a number of occasions but never played past an hour or so (I’m an expert at the first area!). I heard this was ‘Dark Souls Light’ and I welcomed that as I was terrible at DS and would agree that is a fair comparison to be made. Then I discovered my character class rogue/fighter and the game opened up and became a lot more accessible. Finding the class that suits you is key and it has taught me not to just write a game off if I find it too hard.The graphics are fantastic and puts me in the mind of the underrated Space Marine game if set in a high fantasy world that encouraged gruff voices and copious amounts of steroids. Scenery is beautiful and some the PhysX effects are great if you can have them on. The acting is pretty poor and the storyline isn’t going to be winning any awards but it is passable (if you use your imagination and fill in the gaps yourself) and you may as well just pen your own ending or steal one from your favourite book/film.I realise that I’m sounding quite negative towards the game but I’ve given it the ‘thumbs up’ that’s because even though it has a menagerie of things against it, it’s fun. The combat is a flexible and you have to approach every situation carefully depending on what weapon you have equipped and who you are up against. I died…a lot, but this didn’t stop me from returning to the game again and again to get it completed. There was something addictive about the constant punishment and tough battles. I rage quit more than I care to admit but was back to it within fifteen minutes and determined to get past the area. That alone is something of a rarity in games these days, I went back to it and it wasn’t for the storyline.Ultimately, this game should be commended for what it does right and there are a lot of things in that category. If this game is reduced then I would encourage you to pick it up in a heartbeat, look past the flaws and quirky story and you’ve got a gem of a game that shouldn’t be missed."
,Recommended,265300,22247335,"Posted: 4 April, 2016",all,MudDuck,"I had a lot of fun with LOTF. While it's not as engaging as DS2, the visuals are gorgeous and the story is interesting. Combat is not as polished but is still a lot of fun. This game can stand on it's own as a contender in the genre. It took a little while to get the combat mechanics down and the difficulty is a bit erratic. The beginneng of the game is very easy. Almost too easy. Then as you progress through the areas, you realize that since it was so easy in the beginning, you start to have a lot of trouble with some of the enemies about half way in. Then, all of a sudden, the game gets too easy again.Regardless of that, I had a lot of fun with the game. It is a little short and the only reason I have 62 hours on it is because I tried out all of the character types to about the half way point and finihsed the game with the one I liked best. I would say you will get about 25 hours of solid gameplay out of this one."
76561198006659716,Recommended,265300,13398277,"Posted: 15 December, 2014",all,The God Emperor,"For me personally this game can be summed nicely by simply calling it: ""Badass Armor and Weapons the game"".Honestly, every suit of armor and almost every single weapon looks awesome. It seems the developers took the best designs from Darksiders, Warcraft and of course Warhammer mixed them together and created pure concentrated shoulder pauldron badassery. There were times when I slowly walked through an empty corridor carrying a huge sword, a huge shield and wearing armor which would be appropriate for a Space Marine and all I could say was: “I look badass”The light armor in this game makes the ultra-heavy armor in many other rpgs look weak and frail in comparison.Oh… right… I should talk about the gameplay. Considering this game will always be compared to the souls games and pretty much everyone reading this will have played those, I am going to assume that you are a souls player. Personally I would place Lords of the Fallen as far as overall enjoyment is concerned between Demon’s Souls and Dark Souls. It sadly lacks a bit of polish at times but more than makes up for it with meaty heavy combat, great graphics and enemies which, even if some of them are not particularly interesting to fight, still have the benefit of looking cool.Here are a few things this game adds to the souls game formula which can be considered straight up improvements.When you kill enemies you gain experience and you gain a multiplier that will eventually double the experience you get for each kill. This multiplier gets reset every time you die or use a checkpoint. In addition to that you will leave behind all of your collected experience when you die and this experience will decay over time until you retrieve it or die trying. The experience you leave behind heals you when you are in the immediate area and do not pick it up, you can use this give you and edge if you die repeatedly or simply ignore it. Every single attack has a specific timing window which allows you to launch another attack at a reduced stamina cost and light dual wielded weapons have devastating attacks which can only be accessed by getting the timing just right. This greatly rewards those players who can keep a level head even in dire situations. Every single boss has a special way to kill them that usually makes them more challenging to fight. If you successfully complete this challenge you will receive an upgraded version of that boss’s weapon often with a very useful special attack.For better or worse, magic in this game acts just like in dark souls as an easy mode when you know how to use it. If you crave a challenge then do not use magic. There is a single enemy in the entire game that can only be killed using it so you have to invest only a tiny amount of your experience in it.In conclusion I can say that if you like the souls games or like badass spiky armor design then get it as soon as it is available for 40$/Euros. If you have a decent computer you will most likely not regret it."
