,Not Recommended,265300,13653899,"Posted: 27 December, 2014",all,mishugi,trash
,Recommended,265300,28235252,"Posted: 7 December, 2016",all,SkipperSW,"I have never been a big fan of dungeon crawling games that are harder than titanium, but Dark Souls made it change and I was interested. After seeing this game I decided to give it a shot since I did not want to have to play through Dark souls 1, then buy both Dark Souls 2 and 3. If you are considering to follow the Dark Souls series but still want something to ""Prepare"" you, this game is perfect.Dark Souls 1/2/3:- All enemies revive when using Checkpoint or Dying- Barely any Checkpoints throughout the maps- Maps are massive and take long time to find the right path through them- Barely any equipable loot inside chests/containers- Several different classes to choose betweenLords Of The Fallen:- All enemies revive when Dying- A good 15 minutes between checkpoints in every map- Maps are fairly big but still quick to go through early in the game- Plenty of Equipable loot with very nice styles for each class (Currently playing as Warrior and after just 2-3 hours I look like a walking apocalypse, and I've barely gotten anywhere)- *3 classes to choose between with different sets of gear to choose between (I'll explain this after the review)All in all, Lords Of The Fallen shouldn't be seen as ""The game you play before playing Dark Souls"" but should be seen as Lords Of The Fallen. It's a wonderful game with its fair share of♥♥♥♥♥kickery. Responsive controls, smooth movement, beautiful graphics. This game is worth every penny and I think anyone who has ever considered playing Dark Souls, but not dared to, to try this game.I Recommend This Game!*When starting a new game you will be able to create your character through TWO choices:1: Your Magic Type (The kind of Abilities you want your character to have)2: Your Starting Equipment (The type of weapons you'll be wanting to give your character)So when picking Magic Type, you can choose between 3 different options:1: Brawling Magic = Gives you an edge in combat by dishing out more damage2: Deception Magic = Gives you an edge by helping you attack from unseen and doing critical damage3: Solace Magic = Gives you and edge by allowing you to heal and defend yourself better than othersAnd now we come to the second option: Starting Equipment. But there's a bit of an unsuspected feature with these two options! I thought that you HAD to pick Warrior Weapons if you wanted to play as a Warrior. I was wrong! See, when you pick your Magic Type, your character will become 1 of 3 different types! Allow me to explain:Brawling Magic + Warrior Starting Equipment = WarriorBrawling Magic + Rogue Starting Equipment = OutlawBrawling Magic + Cleric Starting Equipment = BrawlerDeception Magic + Warrior Starting Equipment = RaiderDeception Magic + Rogue Starting Equipment = RogueDeception Magic + Cleric Starting Equipment = ExecutionerSolace Magic + Warrior Starting Equipment = PaladinSolace Magic + Rogue Starting Equipment = RangerSolace Magic + Cleric Starting Equipment = ClericNow, depending on whatever decision you make, you'll want to put most of your ability points into the attributes which your character needs! You don't HAVE TO, but if you want to optimize that which your character is best at, then it's the best you should do.Good luck in Lords Of The Fallen!"
