,Not Recommended,265300,20382488,"Posted: 7 January, 2016",all,*711,"While originally the constant crashes, awful performance and odd gameplay put me off of title 900hs, 7 characters and maybe 30 NG cycles in Dark Souls III later I decided to give it a 2nd shot. Said experience is particularly relevant here because I can't detach the two titles since that series (my favorite one ever) is the very reason why I have this game to begin with while at the same time being the very reason this game exists at all.Starting from the place I left the last time… the performance is still subpar (Vsync in particular TANKS my FPS… turning it off gave me +50fps on average Oo) but since the last time I’ve changed my processor and that seems to have sorted out the hard crashes for whatever reason. The gameplay is still odd, it still feels like I’m swimming in tar all the time and inertia seems to have it’s own set of rules in here but I’m happy to say that 10hs in I’m adapted… sort off. There are still some enemy types that make the game a bore to play (namely shielded ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥s) and often times I feel like I’m fighting against the game rather than the enemy (camera angles + GIGANTIC shoulder pads + tight TIGHT corridors + instant spawning enemies RIGHT BY YOUR SIDE =  well… not that fun) which is not ideal to say the least.Coming from DS I’m always looking for epic bosses but they’re nowhere to be found here. While some of them offer some gimmicky mechanic that’s cool to figure out they have no intricacies, ZERO context and no lore whatsoever for 99% of the time. Not to mention they are EASY and this is coming from a person that STILL dies at least twice to the Dancer of the Boreal Valley in every run, in here I died a single time to the champion boss and that was it.Rolling in here is nigh useless. Going light / rogue and practicing A LOT meant that I was able to use it but initial I-frames take quite a while to kick in and stamina cost, distance and speed make it just a subpar choice when compared to going heavy poise + a shield or even better, just get a big weapon and swing away while taking the hits. Fighting methodically was BY FAR less effective than running in spamming R1 so far.When all’s said and done the game still brought me back and still kept me here for this long (I’ll even probably finish it) but be it the LONG adaptation period (that’s mainly increasing your tolerance till you can forgive the game for what it isn’t), the crappy lore or the gameplay itself there hasn’t been a single moment through the entire thing that I thought “this is actually better than playing DSIII again” which ultimately is why I still do not recommend this title even if there’s SOME fun to be had if you like me need something new and are feeling very forgiving."
